e=\"SFrancisco\">{{cite web |url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2016/12/09/san-francisco-film-critics-circle-nominations/ |title=San Francisco Film Critics Circle Nominations! |first=Marshall |last=Flores |date=December 9, 2016 |website=AwardsDaily.com |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SFFCC2016\">{{cite magazine |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/moonlight-named-best-picture-by-san-francisco-film-critics-circle-955302 |title='Moonlight' Named Best Picture by San Francisco Film Critics Circle |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |date=December 12, 2016 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Saturn Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[43rd Saturn Awards|June 28, 2017]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]]\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"SaturnAwards\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/saturn-awards-nominations-2017-rogue-one-walking-dead-1202000833/ |title=Saturn Awards Nominations 2017: 'Rogue One,' 'Walking Dead' Lead |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=March 2, 2017 |magazine=Variety |accessdate=March 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Performance by a Younger Actor|Best Performance by a Younger Actor]]\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[Seattle Film Critics Society]]\n| rowspan=\"7\"| January 5, 2017\n| Best Picture of the Year\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://seattlefilmcritics.com/2016/12/21/the-2016-seattle-film-award-nominees/ |title=The 2016 Seattle Film Award Nominees |date=December 21, 2016 |website=[[Seattle Film Critics Society]] |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://seattlefilmcritics.com/2017/01/05/moonlight-awarded-best-picture-by-seattle-film-critics-society/ |title=\"Moonlight\" Awarded Best Picture by Seattle Film Critics Society |date=January 5, 2017 |website=[[Seattle Film Critics Society]] |accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Robert Eggers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Jarin Blaschke\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| [[Linda Muir]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Best Youth Performance\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Harvey Scrimshaw\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Villain\n| Charlie and Wahab Chaudary <small>(as Black Phillip)</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association]]\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 18, 2016]]\n| Best Horror/Science-Fiction Film\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stlfilmcritics.org/2016-stlfca-annual-award-winners |title=2016 StLFCA Annual Award Winners |date=December 12, 2016 |website=[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Sundance Film Festival]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2015 Sundance Film Festival|February 1, 2015]]\n| Directing Award\n| Robert Eggers\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://twitchfilm.com/2015/02/sundance-2015-award-winners.html |last1=Umstead |first1=Ben |date=January 31, 2015 |title=Sundance 2015 Award Winners |website=[[Twitch Film]] |accessdate=February 1, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208160148/http://twitchfilm.com/2015/02/sundance-2015-award-winners.html |archive-date=December 8, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Grand Jury Prize\n| Robert Eggers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Toronto Film Critics Association]]\n| [[Toronto Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 11, 2016]]\n| Best First Feature\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/moonlight-named-best-film-by-toronto-film-critics-955058 |title='Moonlight' Named Best Film by Toronto Film Critics |last=Vlessing |first=Etan |date=December 12, 2016 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 5, 2016]]\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Breakthrough Performance|Best Youth Performance]]\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wafca.com/awards/2016.htm |title=The 2016 WAFCA Awards |date=December 3, 2016 |website=The Washington, D.C. Area Film Critics Association |accessdate=December 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]]\n| Craig Lathrop\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Witch trials in the early modern period]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|Calvinism|Religion|New England}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://thewitch-movie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4263482|The Witch}}\n* {{Allmovie title|624087|The Witch}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_witch_2016|The Witch}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-witch|The Witch}}\n\n{{Robert Eggers}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Horror}}\n{{Sutherland Trophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch (2015 film)}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2015 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical horror films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Best Horror Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Demons in film]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about child abduction]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1630s]]\n[[Category:Films set in New England]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Matricide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Period horror films]]\n[[Category:Folk horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about Satanism]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Eggers]]\n[[Category:2015 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 film by Robert Eggers}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Witch\n| image          = The Witch poster.png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Robert Eggers]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Rodrigo Teixeira\n* [[Daniel Bekerman]]\n* [[Lars Knudsen (producer)|Lars Knudsen]]\n* Jodi Redmond\n* Jay Van Hoy\n}}\n| writer         = Robert Eggers\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anya Taylor-Joy]]\n* [[Ralph Ineson]]\n* [[Kate Dickie]]\n* Harvey Scrimshaw\n* Ellie Grainger\n* Lucas Dawson\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Korven]]\n| cinematography = [[Jarin Blaschke]]\n| editing        = Louise Ford\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Parts and Labor\n* RT Features\n* Rooks Nest Entertainment\n* Maiden Voyage Pictures\n* Mott Street Pictures\n* Code Red Productions\n* Scythia Films\n* Pulse Films\n* Special Projects\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] (United States)\n* [[Universal Pictures]] (International)\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|1|27|[[2015 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2016|2|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 93 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 92:43--><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/witch-film |title=''The Witch'' (15) |work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=February 18, 2016 |accessdate=February 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/the-witch-c1ef65ab-4fce-45b5-9b7f-0db5e97da59b |title=The Witch |website=Sundance institute |accessdate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n* Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=The Witch |url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/the-witch/5082149.article |first=Tim |last=Grierson |date=January 24, 2015 |work=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2015/01/14/record-breaking-year-canada-2015-sundance-film-festival-10-feature-films |title=Record-breaking year for Canada at the 2015 Sundance Film Festival |date=January 14, 2015 |website=[[Telefilm Canada]] |accessdate=May 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816042835/https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2015/01/14/record-breaking-year-canada-2015-sundance-film-festival-10-feature-films |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n| language       = [[Early Modern English]]\n| budget         = $4 million<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 2017 |title=2016 Feature Film Study |url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/2016_film_study_WEB.pdf |website=Film L.A. Inc. |accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = $40.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=thewitch.htm |title=The Witch (2016) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Witch''''' (also known by its stylized full title,  '''''The VVitch: A New England Folktale''''') is a 2015 [[supernatural horror film]] written and directed by [[Robert Eggers]] in his [[List of directorial debuts|feature directorial debut]]. The film stars [[Anya Taylor-Joy]], [[Ralph Ineson]], [[Kate Dickie]], Harvey Scrimshaw, Ellie Grainger and Lucas Dawson. ''The Witch'' follows a [[Puritan migration to New England (1620\u20131640)|Puritan]] family who encounter forces of evil in the woods beyond their [[New England]] farm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2016/02/the-witch-director-robert-eggers-on-the-real-history-behind-the-movies-most-wtf-scenes.html|title=All The Witch\u2019s Most WTF Moments, Explained: A Spoiler-Filled Interview With the Director|last=Wickman|first=Forrest|date=February 23, 2016|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn international co-production of the United States and Canada, the film premiered at the [[2015 Sundance Film Festival]] on January 27, 2015 and was [[wide release|widely released]] by [[A24 (company)|A24]] on February 19, 2016. The film received positive reviews and was a box office success, grossing $40 million against a budget of $4 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1630s [[New England]], English settler William and his family\u2014wife Katherine, daughter Thomasin, son Caleb, and fraternal twins Mercy and Jonas\u2014are [[excommunication|banished]] from a [[Puritans|Puritan]] [[Plymouth Colony]] over a religious dispute. The family builds a farm near a large, secluded forest and Katherine has a newborn child, Samuel. One day, Thomasin is playing [[peekaboo]] with Samuel when the baby abruptly disappears and it is soon revealed that a [[Witchcraft|witch]] has stolen the [[infant baptism|unbaptized]] Samuel, killing him and using his remains to make a [[flying ointment]].<ref name=\"ATWMWTFME\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/02/23/the_witch_director_robert_eggers_on_the_real_history_behind_the_movie_s.html |title=All The Witch's Most WTF Moments, Explained: A Spoiler-Filled Interview With the Director |last1=Wickman |first1=Forrest |last2=Eggers |first2=Robert |date=February 23, 2016 |magazine=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKatherine, devastated by Samuel's disappearance, spends her days crying and praying. While hunting with William, Caleb asks if Samuel's unbaptized soul will reach [[Heaven]]. William encourages Caleb to not raise the question and later reveals to Caleb that he traded Katherine's silver cup for hunting supplies. That night, Katherine questions Thomasin about the disappearance of her cup and suspects her to be responsible for Samuel's abduction. After the children retire to bed, they overhear their parents discussing sending Thomasin away to serve another family.\n\nEarly the next morning, Thomasin finds Caleb preparing to check a trap in the forest and forces him to take her with him by threatening to awaken their parents. In the woods, the two spot a hare, which sends their horse into a panic and their dog Fowler promptly chases. Caleb pursues, while the horse throws Thomasin off, knocking her unconscious. Caleb becomes lost in the woods and stumbles upon Fowler's disemboweled body. Deep in the woods, he comes across a hovel, where a beautiful young woman emerges and seduces him.  Once Caleb is close enough, however, the woman's arm becomes old and decrepit and grabs Caleb. William finds Thomasin and takes her home where Katherine angrily chastises Thomasin for taking Caleb into the woods before William reluctantly admits that he sold Katherine's cup. Katherine does not allow Thomasin the chance to explain that she was there to help keep watch over Caleb.\n\nLater that evening, Caleb has found his way home and Thomasin discovers him outdoors in the rain, naked and delirious from an unknown illness. When he awakens the next day, Caleb expels a bloody apple from his mouth; Katherine believes it to be [[Christian views on witchcraft|witchcraft]]. Caleb passionately proclaims his love to Christ before he dies, though Katherine believes Caleb to have been under some sort of spell. The twins then accuse Thomasin of witchcraft and, in retaliation, Thomasin reveals to the parents that the twins have had conversations with Black Phillip, the family's [[British primitive goat|billy goat]]. Enraged, William boards both Thomasin and the twins inside the goat house. Thomasin overhears William break down and confess to God that he has been [[pride]]ful and made his family leave their old village out of stubbornness rather than sincere religious devotion. Later in the night, the three children are woken by the sounds of rustling in the goat house and discover an old woman drinking milk from the goats. Meanwhile, inside the house, Katherine awakens to a vision of Caleb holding Samuel. After a brief discussion, Caleb offers Samuel to Katherine so she may breast feed the baby but the baby is shown to be in fact a crow that is pecking away at her breast.\n\nThe next day William awakens and walks outside to find the stable destroyed, the goats eviscerated, the twins missing and an unconscious Thomasin lying nearby with blood-stained hands. As Thomasin awakens, Black Phillip gores William before her eyes. An unhinged Katherine, who now blames Thomasin for the tragedies that have beset the family and accusing her of trying to seduce William and Caleb, attacks Thomasin, who kills her mother with a cleaver in self-defense.\n\nAlone, Thomasin enters the stable and urges Black Phillip to speak to her. The goat responds by asking if Thomasin would like to \"live deliciously\" and materializes into a [[Satan|tall, devilishly handsome, black-clad man]]. Black Phillip orders Thomasin to remove her clothes and to sign her name in a book that appears before her. Thomasin follows Black Phillip into the forest, where she joins a [[coven]] of witches holding a [[Witches' Sabbath]] around a bonfire. The coven begins to levitate and a laughing Thomasin joins them, ascending above the trees.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Anya Taylor-Joy]] as Thomasin\n* [[Ralph Ineson]] as William\n* [[Kate Dickie]] as Katherine\n* Harvey Scrimshaw as Caleb\n* Ellie Grainger as Mercy\n* Lucas Dawson as Jonas\n* [[Julian Richings]] as The Governor\n* Bathsheba Garnett as Witch\n* [[Sarah Stephens]] as Young Witch\n* Charlie as Black Phillip (goat form)<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/black-phillip-real-story-behind-871974 |title=Black Phillip: The Real Story Behind the Breakout Goat From 'The Witch' |date=March 2, 2016 |last=Abramovitch |first=Seth |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref>\n* Wahab Chaudhry as Black Phillip (voice, human form)\n* Axtun Henry Dube and Athan Conrad Dube as Samuel\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nEggers, who was born in New Hampshire, was inspired to write the film by his childhood fascination with [[witchcraft|witches]] and frequent visits to the [[Plimoth Plantation]] as a schoolboy. After unsuccessfully pitching films that were \"too weird, too obscure\", Eggers realized that he would have to make a more conventional film.<ref name=\"Indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://indiewire.com/article/how-robert-eggers-combined-history-and-childhood-horrors-in-the-witch-20151021 |title=How Robert Eggers Combined History and Childhood Horrors in 'The Witch' |last1=Anielski |first1=Ryan |date=October 21, 2015 |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> He said at a Q&A, \"If I'm going to make a genre film, it has to be personal and it has to be good.\"<ref name=\"Indiewire\"/> The production team worked extensively with British and American museums, as well as consulting experts on 17th-century British agriculture.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bitel |first=Anton |title=Voices of the Undead: Robert Eggers on The Witch |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/interviews/robert-eggers-witch |date=March 11, 2016 |magazine=[[Sight & Sound]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nEggers wanted to film the picture on location in New England but the lack of [[tax incentives]] meant he had to settle for Canada.<ref name=\"Indiewire\"/> This proved to be something of a problem for Eggers, because he could not find the forest environment he was looking for in the country.<ref name=\"Indiewire\"/> They had to go \"off the map\", eventually finding a location ([[Kiosk, Ontario]]) that was \"extremely remote\"; Eggers said that the nearest town \"made New Hampshire look like a metropolis\".<ref name=\"Indiewire\"/>\n\nThe casting took place in England, as Eggers wanted authentic accents to represent a family newly arrived in Plymouth.<ref name=\"vnews\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Nicola |title=New Hampshire Director Sifts His Home Soil |url=https://www.vnews.com/Archives/2016/03-Filler/EggersQandA-ns-vn-031816 |accessdate=July 22, 2018 |work=[[Valley News]] |date=March 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn order to give the film an authentic look, Eggers shot only \"with natural light and indoors, the only lighting was candles\". Eggers also chose the spelling of the film's title as \"''The VVitch''\" in its title sequence and on posters, stating that he found this spelling in a [[Jacobean era]] pamphlet on witchcraft, along with other period texts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.format.com/magazine/features/design/the-witch-robert-eggers-movie-interview |title=Designer-Turned-Director Robert Eggers Discusses His Horror Film 'The Witch' |last1=Bloom |first1=Jessica |date=March 15, 2016 |magazine=Format |accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, costume designer [[Linda Muir]] joined the crew, and consulted 35 books in the ''Clothes of the Common People in Elizabethan and Early Stuart England'' series to plan the costumes. The costumes were made with wool, linen, or hemp. Muir also lobbied for a larger costume budget.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://brightlightsfilm.com/dressing-witch-interview-costume-designer-linda-muir/# |title=Dressing The Witch: An Interview with Costume Designer Linda Muir |last=Ankenbauer |first=Sam |date=May 27, 2016 |work=[[Bright Lights Film Journal]] |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Mark Korven]] wrote the film's score, which aimed to be \"tense and dissonant\", while focusing on minimalism. Eggers vetoed the use of any electronic instruments and \"didn't want any traditional harmony or melody in the score\", and so Korven chose to create music with atypical instruments, including the [[nyckelharpa]] and the [[waterphone]]. He knew that the director liked to retain a degree of creative control, so he relied on loose play centered on improvisation \"so that [Eggers] could move notes around whenever he wanted\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/interviews/3381360/we-interviewed-composer-mark-korven-about-his-terrifying-score-for-the-witch/ |title=We Interviewed Composer Mark Korven About His Terrifying Score for 'The Witch' |last=Barkan |first=Jonathan |date=February 26, 2016 |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nofilmschool.com/2016/09/mark-korven-composer-the-witch |title=How Mark Korven Avoided the Temptations of Temp Music to Score 'The Witch' |last=Fusco |first=Jon |date=September 16, 2016 |website=No Film School.com |accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[2015 Sundance Film Festival]], on January 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/premiere-and-doc-premiere-films-and-special-events-announced-for-2015-festival |title=Sundance Institute Announces Films in Premieres and Documentary Premieres for 2015 Sundance Film Festival |date=December 8, 2014 |website=[[Sundance Institute]] |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sundance.org/projects/the-witch-c1ef65ab-4fce-45b5-9b7f-0db5e97da59b |title=The Witch |website=Sundance Film Festival |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> The film was also screened in the Special Presentations section of the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]], on September 18, 2015.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sandra-bullocks-our-brand-tom-hiddlestons-i-saw-the-light-to-premiere-at-toronto-1201572271/ |title=Sandra Bullock's 'Our Brand Is Crisis,' Robert Redford's 'Truth' to Premiere at Toronto |last=Punter |first=Jennie |date=August 18, 2015 |magazine=Variety |accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tiff.net/festivals/festival15/specialpresentations/the-witch |title=The Witch |website=TIFF.net |accessdate=February 16, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124121232/http://tiff.net/festivals/festival15/specialpresentations/the-witch |archivedate=January 24, 2016 }}</ref> [[A24 (company)|A24]] and [[DirecTV Cinema]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewrap.com/sundance-a24-directv-nearing-deal-for-robert-eggers-the-witch/ |title=Sundance: A24, DirecTV Buy Robert Eggers' 'The Witch' (Updated) |first=Jeff|last=Sneider |date=January 24, 2015 |website=[[TheWrap]] |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> The film received very positive reactions in advance screenings, so the studios decided to give the film a wide theatrical release in the United States, on February 19, 2016.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/box-office/deadpool-box-office-the-witch-1201708282/ |title=Box Office: 'Deadpool' Still a Juggernaut; 'The Witch' Generating Heat |first=Brent|last=Lang |date=February 17, 2016 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/deadpool-risen-the-witch-race-weekend-box-office-1201705730/ |title='Deadpool' Destroying Rivals With $56M Weekend; 'Risen' Burning 'Witch' |first=Alexander|last=D'Alessandro |date=February 19, 2016 |magazine=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released on [[Blu-ray]] and digital HD on May 17, 2016 in the USA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7681/the-witch |title=The Witch |website=DVDsReleaseDates.com |accessdate=May 7, 2016}}</ref> The discs' extras include outtakes, audio commentary, a documentary\u2014''The Witch: A Primal Folktale'', which summarizes the cast and crew's making of the film\u2014and a 30-minute question-and-answer session filmed in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] featuring director Eggers, lead actress Anya Taylor-Joy, and historians Richard Trask and Brunonia Barry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/159107/20160517/review-witch-blu-ray-adds-historical-context-one-unique-horror.htm |title=Review: 'The Witch' Blu-Ray Adds Historical Context To One Of The Most Unique Horror Films In Years |first=Jason |last=Serafino |date=May 17, 2016 |website=Tech Times |accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> A [[4K Ultra HD Blu-ray]] was released on April 23, 2019.<ref>https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Witch-4K-Blu-ray/231318/</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Witch'' grossed $25.1 million in the United States and Canada and $15.3 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $40.4 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn North America, pre-release tracking suggested that the film would gross $5\u20137 million from 2,046 theaters in its opening weekend, trailing fellow newcomer ''[[Risen (2016 film)|Risen]]'' ($7\u201312 million projection) but similar to opener ''[[Race (2016 film)|Race]]'' ($4\u20137 million projection).<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/deadpool-race-risen-witch-box-office-preview-1201704419/ |title='Deadpool' Still Cool In Weekend 2 With Superhero Set To Pass $200M \u2013 Box Office Preview |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=February 17, 2016 |work=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> The film grossed $3.3 million on its first day and $8.8 million in its opening weekend, finishing fourth at the box office behind ''[[Deadpool (film)|Deadpool]]'' ($56.5 million), ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]'' ($12.5 million) and ''Risen'' ($11.8 million).<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/deadpool-risen-the-witch-race-weekend-box-office-1201705730/ |title='Deadpool' Strong With Second Weekend Of $55M; 'Risen' Takes $11.8M, 'Witch' At $8.7M |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |date=February 21, 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 90% based on 317 reviews, with an average rating of 7.77/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"As thought-provoking as it is visually compelling, ''The Witch'' delivers a deeply unsettling exercise in slow-building horror that suggests great things for debuting writer-director Robert Eggers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_witch_2016|title=The Witch (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports a weighted average score of 83 out of 100, based on 46 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Meta\">{{metacritic film|the-witch}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 55% overall positive score and a 41% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening/>\n\nWriting in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Justin Chang commented that \"A fiercely committed ensemble and an exquisite sense of historical detail conspire to cast a highly atmospheric spell in ''The Witch'', a strikingly achieved tale of a mid-17th-century New England family's steady descent into religious hysteria and madness.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/sundance-film-review-the-witch-1201411310/ |title=Sundance Film Review: 'The Witch' |last=Chang |first=Justin |date=January 23, 2015 |magazine=Variety |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Yohana Desta of ''[[Mashable]]'' stated that ''The Witch'' is a \"stunningly crafted experience that'll have you seeking out a church as soon as you leave the theater\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2016/02/16/the-witch-review/#aYJHIG06qiqu |title='The Witch' is a film so f*cked up, Satan would see it twice |last=Desta |first=Yohana |date=February 18, 2016 | website=[[Mashable]].com |language=English |accessdate=February 21, 2016}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]], in his ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' review, gave the film 3{{1/2}} stars, and wrote of the film: \"Building his film on the diabolical aftershocks of Puritan repression, Eggers raises ''The Witch'' far above the horror herd. He doesn't need cheap tricks. Eggers merely directs us to look inside.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-witch-20160218 |title='The Witch' Movie Review |last=Travers |first=Peter |date=February 18, 2016 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Stephanie Zacharek summarized the movie in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as \"a triumph of tone\", writing that \"Although Eggers is extremely discreet\u2014the things you don't see are more horrifying than those you do\u2014the picture's relentlessness sometimes feels like torment.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://time.com/4226147/review-the-witch-new-england-folktale/ |title='The Witch' Movie Review: A Supercreepy New England Folktale |first=Stephanie |last=Zacharek |date=February 16, 2016 |magazine=TIME |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Gregory Wakeman, writing for CinemaBlend, rated it five stars, writing that \"[its] acting, lighting, music, writing, production design, cinematography, editing, and direction all immediately impress. While, at the same time, they combine to create an innately bewitching tale that keeps you on tenterhooks all the way up until its grandiose but enthralling finale.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cinemablend.com/reviews/Witch-69327.html |title=The Witch |first=Gregory |last=Wakeman |date=January 2015 |website=Cinemablend |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Ann Hornaday wrote in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that the film joins the ranks of horror films such as ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'', ''[[The Omen (1976 film)|The Omen]]'', and ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'', saying that ''The Witch'' \"comports itself less like an imitator of those classics than their progenitor... a tribute to a filmmaker who, despite his newcomer status, seems to have arrived in the full throes of maturity, in full control of his prodigious powers.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/17th-century-horror-film-the-witch-creeps-you-out-long-after-credits-roll/2016/02/18/6b50732a-d4c7-11e5-b195-2e29a4e13425_story.html?tid=kp_google |title=17th-century horror film 'The Witch' creeps you out long after credits roll |last=Hornaday |first=Ann |date=February 18, 2015 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Jay Bauman of [[RedLetterMedia]] named the film his favorite film of 2016, labelling it \"a masterpiece\".\n\nHowever, some critics as well as audiences were less pleased with the film; Ethan Sacks, of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', wrote that while the film does not suffer from the cinematography, acting, or setting, early on it \"seems that ''The Witch'' is tapping a higher metaphor for coming of age...or religious intolerance...or man's uneasy balance with nature...or something. It doesn't take long into the film's hour and a half running time, however, to break that spell.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/witch-casts-spell-critics-not-good-article-1.2529738 |title='The Witch' casts a spell on critics though it's not good |first=Ethan |last=Sacks |date=February 17, 2016 |newspaper=New York Daily News |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Critics have noted that the film has received backlash from audiences regarding the film's themes and slow approach to horror;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3789611 |title=Is The Witch Really a Horror Movie? |date=February 18, 2016 |website=MoviePilot.com |accessdate=April 26, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304013735/https://moviepilot.com/posts/3789611 |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Lesley Coffin criticized [[A24 (company)|A24]], saying it was \"a huge mistake\" to market ''The Witch'' as a terrifying horror film:\n\n{{blockquote|Not because it doesn't fit into the genre of horror, but because of the power of expectations. The less you know about this movie the better your experience will be, but everyone who saw it opening weekend probably walked in with too much knowledge and hype to really get as much out of it as they could have if the film had the veil of mystery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themarysue.com/the-witch-review-beware-of-high-expectations |title=The Witch Review: Beware of High Expectations |last=Coffin |first=Lesley |date=February 22, 2016 |website=The Mary Sue |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n''[[HitFix]]'' writer Chris Eggertson was critical of mainstream Hollywood; he said that ''The Witch'' \"got under [his] skin profoundly\", though he argued that it \"did not have the moment-to-moment, audience-pleasing shocks that moviegoers have become accustomed to thanks to movies like ''[[Sinister (film)|Sinister]]'' and ''[[The Purge (2013 film)|The Purge]]'' and ''[[Paranormal Activity (film)|Paranormal Activity]]'' and every other [[Blumhouse]] and [[Platinum Dunes]] title in the canon.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/why-do-so-many-horror-fans-hate-the-witch |title=Why do so many horror fans hate The Witch? |last=Eggertsen |first=Chris |date=February 22, 2016 |website=Hitfix.com |accessdate=April 26, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302063432/http://www.hitfix.com/news/why-do-so-many-horror-fans-hate-the-witch |archive-date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHorror authors [[Stephen King]] and [[Brian Keene]] both reacted positively towards the film; King tweeted significant praise for the film, stating, \"''The Witch'' scared the hell out of me. And it's a real movie, tense and thought-provoking as well as visceral\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3380009/stephen-king/ |title='The Witch' Scared the Hell Out of Stephen King! |first=Brad |last=Miska |date=February 16, 2016 |website=Bloody Disgusting |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> while Keene, on social media, stated, \"''The Witch'' is a gorgeous, thoughtful, scary horror film that 90% of the people in the theater with you will be too stupid to understand.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BrianKeene |last=Keene |first=Brian |number=701391382275952641 |title=THE WITCH is a gorgeous, thoughtful, scary horror film that 90% of the people in the theater with you will be too stupid to understand. |date=February 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\nJason Coffman expressed his \"frustration\" toward viewers who felt ''The Witch'' was \"boring\", saying:\n\n{{blockquote|[T]hese detractors have targeted [these] films that work within the genre but are also examples of how genre cinema can explore concepts and themes in ways that less fantastic stories cannot. In short, the rejection of these films appears to people outside of horror fandom as a rejection of cinema as an art form.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/cinenation-show/this-is-why-we-can-t-have-nice-things-the-witch-and-horror-fandom-s-gatekeepers-b2c0bb0d8f9a#.pmdzppoe2 |title=This is why we can't have nice things: \"The Witch\" and horror fandom's gatekeepers |first=Jason |last= Coffman |date=February 19, 2016 |website=[[Medium.com]] |accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n====Religious====\nJulia Alexander of ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' states that ''The Witch'' \"asks people to try and understand what life would have been like for a family of devout Christians living in solitude, terrified of what may happen if they go against the [[Bible|word of God]]\".<ref name=Alexander2016>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/17/11034540/the-witch-review-a-terrifying-tale-of-depravity |title=The Witch review: A terrifying tale of depravity |last=Alexander |first=Julia |date=February 17, 2016 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |language=English |accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The Atlantic]]'', Alissa Wilkinson stated that many films featured at the 2015 Sundance Film Festival\u2014''The Witch'', along with ''[[Last Days in the Desert]]'', ''[[Don Verdean]]'', and ''[[I Am Michael]]''\u2014reveal a \"resurgence of interest in the religious\" and described ''The Witch'' as \"a chilling circa-1600 story of the [[Devil in Christianity|devil]] taking over a devout, [[Christian biblical canons|Scripture]]-quoting family\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/03/not-your-typical-god-movie/385315/ |title=Can Indie Filmmakers Save Religious Cinema? |last=Wilkinson |first=Alissa |date=March 18, 2015 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=February 23, 2016 |quote=''[[Last Days in the Desert]]'' was the obvious \u201cBible film\u201d at this year's Sundance. But the festival's lineup revealed a resurgence of interest in the religious: In ''[[Don Verdean]]'', an affectionately satirical comedy, [[Sam Rockwell]] stars as a \u201cBiblical archaeologist\u201d who becomes a pawn in a war between two rival local ministers. ''The Witch'', a pristine horror debut from writer/director Robert Eggers, is a chilling circa-1600 story of the devil taking over a devout, Scripture-quoting family. ''[[I Am Michael]]'', executive produced by [[Gus Van Sant]], tells the true story of Michael Glatze (played by James Franco), a former gay activist who denounced homosexuality and became a Christian pastor. Other films like ''[[Z for Zachariah (film)|Z for Zachariah]]'' and ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl|Me, Earl, and the Dying Girl]]'' subtly draw on questions and motifs that animate Biblical narratives and questions.}}</ref> [[Eve Tushnet]] commented in an article in ''[[The American Conservative|TAC]]'', which was also published in ''[[First Things]]'', that ''The Witch''{{'}}s view of witchcraft is \"not revisionist\" and further states that the film is \"pervaded by the [[fear of God]]. There are occasional references to His [[mercy]] but only as something to beg for, not something to trust in\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/out-in-the-fields-with-God/ |title=Out in the Fields with God |last=Tushnet |first=Eve |date=February 26, 2016 |magazine=[[The American Conservative]] |accessdate=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/blogs/firstthoughts/2016/03/first-links-3416 |title=First Links \u2014 3.4.16 |last=Tushnet |first=Eve |date=March 4, 2016 |website=[[First Things]].com |accessdate=March 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA review by Adam R. Holz on ''Plugged In'', a publication of the [[Christian fundamentalism|conservative Christian]] organisation [[Focus on the Family]], heavily criticised the film, stating that:\n\n{{blockquote|William is absolutely devoted to leading his family in holiness and the ways of the Lord, which should be a good thing. But the fruit of William's rigorous focus on dogmatic piety isn't a lifting of burdens, which we're told should happen in {{Bibleverse|Matthew|11:30|KJV}}, or a joyful celebration of living life to the fullest, as is referenced in {{Bibleverse|John|10:10|KJV}}; rather it is deep fear and morbid meditations on hell, damnation and the forces of spiritual darkness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pluggedin.com/movie-reviews/the-witch-2016/ |title=The Witch Movie Review (2016) |year=2015 |website=[[Plugged In]] |accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nJosh Larsen of ''Think Christian'', however, offered a Christian explanation of the conclusion of the film, stating that in \"encountering evil, the family in the film veers wildly back and forth between 'triumphalism' and 'defeatism,' two theological extremes\" and \"in refusing to allow for [[Grace in Christianity|grace]], they become easy pickings for the witch\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkchristian.reframemedia.com/should-christians-be-afraid-of-the-witch |title=Should Christians be afraid of The Witch? |last=Larsen |first=Josh |date=February 24, 2016 |website=Think Christian |accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nEmily VanDerWerff of [[Vox (website)|Vox]] stated that:\n\n{{blockquote|A24 could have just as easily courted the approval of, say, [[Christian theology|theologians]] who have a fondness for [[Calvinism]]. ''The VVitch'' takes place in Colonial America, and it unfolds from the perspective of period Christians who genuinely believe the woods around their tiny farm contain some sort of evil, supernatural being\u2014and are ultimately proved correct.<ref name=VanDerWerff>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/2/18/11049790/the-witch-satan-satanism |title=Why Satanists have given new horror movie The Witch their endorsement |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |date=February 18, 2016 |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |language=English |accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:small\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Date of ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{nowrap|{{Abbr|Ref(s)|References}}}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 28, 2016]]\n| Best First Film\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardswatch.com/news/austin-film-critics-association-afca-nominations-the-handmaiden-lands-top-mentions-trevante-rhodes-double-nominated/ |title=Austin Film Critics Association (AFCA) Nominations: The Handmaiden Lands Top Mentions, Trevante Rhodes Double Nominated |first=Erik |last=Anderson |date=December 15, 2016 |website=AwardsWatch.com |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/austin-film-critics-association/2016-nominations-5307a85b7c6a#.yjh64hs3i |title=2016 Austin Film Critics Awards Nominees, 'Moonlight' and 'Arrival' lead the way in AFCA's 2016 nominations |first=Neil |last=Miller |date=December 15, 2016 |website=Medium.com |accessdate=December 15, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622043509/https://austinfilmcritics.org/2016-nominations-5307a85b7c6a?gi=99f3d4c637ab |archive-date=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Breakthrough Artist Award\n| [[Anya Taylor-Joy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 2016|December 11, 2016]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best New Filmmaker|Best New Filmmaker]]\n| [[Robert Eggers]]\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/la-la-land-named-best-picture-by-boston-society-film-critics-955066 |title='La La Land' Named Best Picture by Boston Society of Film Critics |first=Patrick |last=Shanley |date=December 11, 2016 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Bram Stoker Awards]]\n| April 29, 2017\n| Superior Achievement in a Screenplay\n| Robert Eggers\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://horrorworld.org/2016-bram-stoker-awards-final-ballot/ |title=2016 Bram Stoker Awards Final Ballot |first=Angela |last=Bennett |date=February 23, 2017 |website=Horror World |accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Chicago Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 15, 2016]]\n| Best Art Direction\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/component/content/article/148-cfca-nominees-2016 |title=The 2016 Chicago Film Critics Association Award Nominees |date=December 11, 2016 |website=[[Chicago Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220200944/http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/component/content/article/148-cfca-nominees-2016 |archivedate=December 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Most Promising Filmmaker\n| Robert Eggers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics Choice Awards]]\n| [[22nd Critics' Choice Awards|December 11, 2016]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Sci-Fi/Horror Movie|Best Sci-Fi/Horror Movie]]\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-awards |title=La La Land Leads with 12 Nominations for the 22nd Annual Critics' Choice Awards |date=December 1, 2016 |website=Critics' Choice |accessdate=December 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203144845/http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-awards/ |archive-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Empire Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[22nd Empire Awards|March 19, 2017]]\n| [[Empire Award for Best Horror|Best Horror]]\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://empireonline.com/movies/news/three-empire-awards-2017-rogue-one-tom-hiddleston-patrick-stewart-win-big/ |title=Three Empire Awards 2017: Rogue One, Tom Hiddleston and Patrick Stewart Win Big |last=Nugent |first=John |date=March 19, 2017 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |access-date=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Empire Award for Best Female Newcomer|Best Female Newcomer]]\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| October 2, 2017<ref name=\"FANGORIA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-winners-and-full-results/ |title=The 2017 Fangoria Chainsaw Awards Winners and Full Results! |date=October 2, 2017 |website=[[Fangoria]] |accessdate=October 9, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214193332/http://www.fangoria.com/new/the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-winners-and-full-results/ |archivedate=December 14, 2017 }}</ref>\n| Best Film\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"FANGORIA\"/>\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| [[Ralph Ineson]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best Score\n| Mark Korven\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Rotten Tomatoes|Golden Tomato Awards]]\n| January 12, 2017\n| Best Horror Movie 2016\n| ''The Witch''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/best-horror-movie-2016/ |title=Golden Tomato Awards - Best-Reviewed Horror Movies 2016 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Golden Trailer Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| May 4, 2016\n| Best Horror\n| \"Family\"\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"GTA17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goldentrailer.com/gta17_nominees/ |title=The 17th Annual Golden Trailer Award Nominees |work=Golden Trailer.com |accessdate=October 27, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110070412/http://www.goldentrailer.com/gta17_nominees/ |archive-date=November 10, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Horror TV Spot\n| \"Life\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing in a TV Spot\n| \"Paranoia\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Gotham Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2016|November 28, 2016]]\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Breakthrough Actor]]\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"GothamAward\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gotham-awards-nominations-2016-list-nominees-1201895205/?platform=hootsuite |title=Gotham Awards Nominations 2016: 'Manchester By The Sea' Leads with Four |last=Cox |first=Gordon |date=October 20, 2016 |magazine=Variety |accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\