ch''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/moonlight-named-best-film-by-toronto-film-critics-955058 |title='Moonlight' Named Best Film by Toronto Film Critics |last=Vlessing |first=Etan |date=December 12, 2016 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 5, 2016]]\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Breakthrough Performance|Best Youth Performance]]\n| Anya Taylor-Joy\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wafca.com/awards/2016.htm |title=The 2016 WAFCA Awards |date=December 3, 2016 |website=The Washington, D.C. Area Film Critics Association |accessdate=December 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]]\n| Craig Lathrop\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Witch trials in the early modern period]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|Calvinism|Religion|New England}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://thewitch-movie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4263482|The Witch}}\n* {{Allmovie title|624087|The Witch}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_witch_2016|The Witch}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-witch|The Witch}}\n\n{{Robert Eggers}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Horror}}\n{{Sutherland Trophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch (2015 film)}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2015 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical horror films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Best Horror Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Demons in film]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about child abduction]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1630s]]\n[[Category:Films set in New England]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Matricide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Period horror films]]\n[[Category:Folk horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about Satanism]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Eggers]]\n[[Category:2015 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "ScottSullivan1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Witch_(2015_film)"}
{"title_page": "Iron(II) hydride", "text_new": "{{chembox\n| Name = Iron(II) hydride\n| SystematicName = Dihydridoiron(4\u2022)\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo = 33485-98-2\n| CASNo_Ref = \n| PubChem = 141155\n\n| SMILES = [FeH2]\n| ChemSpiderID = 124509\n| StdInChI = 1S/Fe.2H\n| StdInChIKey = FUEZNWLRTWZOHC-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = FeH<sub>2</sub><sup>4\u2022</sup>\n| MolarMass = 57.861 g mol<sup>\u22121</sup>\n}}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherCompounds = [[iron hydride]]s, [[Iron(I) hydride|FeH]], [[FeH3]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Iron(II) hydride''', systematically named '''iron dihydride''' and '''poly(dihydridoiron)''' is solid [[inorganic compound]] with the [[chemical formula]] {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}} (also written {{Chem|([FeH|2|]}})<sub>''n''</sub> or {{Chem|FeH|2}}). ). It is kinetically unstable at ambient temperature, and as such, little is known about its bulk properties. However, it known as a black, amorphous powder, which was synthesised for the first time in 2014.<ref name=\"Morris2014\">{{Cite journal|last1=Morris|first1=Leah|last2=Trudeau|first2=Michel L.|last3=Lees|first3=Martin R.|last4=Hanna|first4=John V.|last5=Antonelli|first5=David M.|date=25 March 2014|title=On the path to bulk {{Chem|FeH|2}}: Synthesis and magnetic properties of amorphous iron(II) hydride|journal=Journal of Alloys and Compounds|volume=590|pages=199\u2013204|doi=10.1016/j.jallcom.2013.12.099}}</ref>\n\nIron(II) hydride is the second simplest polymeric iron hydride (after [[iron(I) hydride]]). Due to its instability, it has no practical industrial uses. However, in [[metallurgy|metallurgical]] chemistry, iron(II) hydride is fundamental to certain forms of [[iron-hydrogen alloy]]s.\n\n== Nomenclature ==\n\nThe systematic name ''iron dihydride'', a valid [[IUPAC]] name, is constructed according to the compositional nomenclature. However, as the name is compositional in nature, it does not distinguish between compounds of the same stoichiometry, such as molecular species, which exhibit distinct chemical properties. The systematic names ''poly(dihydridoiron)'' and ''poly[ferrane(2)]'', also valid IUPAC names, are constructed according to the additive and electron-deficient substitutive nomenclatures, respectively. They do distinguish the titular compound from the others.\n\n== Dihydridoiron ==\n\n[[File:Linear-3D-balls.png|150px|thumb|right]]\nDihydridoiron, also systematically named ferrane(2), is a related inorganic compound with the chemical formula {{Chem|FeH|2}} (also written {{Chem|[FeH|2|]}}). It is both kinetically unstable at concentration and at ambient temperature.\n\nDihydridoiron is the second simplest molecular iron hydride (after hydridoiron), and is also the progenitor of clusters with the same stoichiometry. In addition, it may be considered to be the iron(II) hydride monomer.\n\nIt has been observed in [[matrix isolation]].<ref name=\"Koersgen\">Helga K\u00f6rsgen, Petra M\u00fcrtz, Klaus Lipus, Wolfgang Urban, Jonathan P. Towle, John M. Brown (1996), \"[https://aip.scitation.org/doi/pdf/10.1063/1.471180 The identification of the {{chem|FeH|2}} radical in the gas phase by infrared spectroscopy]\".{{Closed access}} [[J. Chem. Phys.|The Journal of Chemical Physics]], volume 104, issue 12, page 4859 {{ISSN|0021-9606}} {{doi|10.1063/1.471180}}\n</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\n\n=== Acidity and basicity ===\n\nAn electron pair of a Lewis base can join with the iron centre in dihydridoiron by adduction:\n:{{Chem|[FeH|2|]}} + :L \u2192 {{Chem|[FeH|2|L]}}\nBecause of this capture of an adducted [[electron pair]], dihydridoiron has Lewis acidic character. Dihydridoiron has the capacity to capture up to four electron pairs from Lewis bases.\n\nA proton can join with the iron centre by dissociative protonation:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|H|+}} \u2192 {{Chem|FeH|+}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nBecause dissociative protonation involves the capture of the [[proton]] ({{Chem|H|+}}) to form a Kubas complex ({{Chem|[FeH(H|2|)}}]<sup>+</sup>) as an intermediate, dihydridoiron and its adducts of weak-field Lewis bases, such as water, also have Br\u00f8nsted\u2013Lowry basic character. They have the capacity to capture up to two protons. Its dissociated [[conjugate acid]]s are hydridoiron(1+) and iron(2+) ({{Chem|FeH|+}} and {{Chem|Fe|2+}}).\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}} {{Eqm}} {{Chem|FeH|+}} + {{Chem|H|2|O}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nAqueous solutions of adducts of weak-field Lewis bases are however, unstable due to hydrolysis of the dihydridoiron and hydridoiron(1+) groups:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2|O}} \u2192 {{Chem|Fe(OH)|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}}\n:{{Chem|FeH|+}} + 3&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2|O}} \u2192 {{Chem|Fe(OH)|2}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nIt should be expected that iron dihydride clusters and iron(II) hydride have similar acid-base properties, although reaction rates and equilibrium constants are different.\n\nAlternatively, a hydrogen centre in the dihydridoiron group in adducts of strong-field Lewis bases, such as carbon monoxide, may separate from the molecule by ionisation:\n:{{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H|2|]}} \u2192 {{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H]|-}} + {{Chem|H|+}}\nBecause of this release of the proton, adducts of strong-field Lewis bases have may have Br\u00f8nsted\u2013Lowry acidic character. They have the capacity to release up to two protons.\n:{{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H|2|]}} +{{Chem|H|2|O}} {{Eqm}} {{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H]|-}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}}\nMixed adducts with Lewis bases of differing fields strengths may exhibit intermediate behaviour.<ref name=\"Basallote1998\">{{cite journal|last1=Basallote|first1=Manuel G.|last2=Dur\u00e1n|first2=Joaqu\u00edn|last3=Fern\u00e1ndez-Trujillo|first3=M. Jes\u00fas|last4=M\u00e1\u00f1ez|first4=M. Angeles|date=1998|title=Kinetics of protonation of ''cis''-[{{Chem|FeH|2}}(dppe){{sub|2}}]: Formation of the dihydrogen complex ''trans''-[{{Chem|[FeH(H|2|)}}(dppe){{sub|2}}]+ (dppe = {{Chem|Ph|2|PCH|2|CH|2|PPh|2}})|journal=[[Dalton Trans.|Journal of the Chemical Society, Dalton Transactions]]|volume=0|issue=13|pages=2205\u20132210|doi=10.1039/A800916C}}</ref>\n\n=== Structure ===\n\nIn iron(II) hydride, the atoms form a network, individual atoms being interconnected by [[covalent bond]]s. Since it is a polymeric solid, a monocrystalline sample is not expected to undergo state transitions, such as melting and dissolution, as this would require the rearrangement of molecular bonds and consequently, change its chemical identity. Colloidal crystalline samples, wherein intermolecular forces are relevant, are expected to undergo state transitions.<ref name=\"Pieranski2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Pieranski|first1=Pawel|date=20 August 2006|title=Colloidal crystals|journal=[[Contemp. Phys.|Contemporary Physics]]|volume=24|issue=1|pages=25\u201373|doi=10.1080/00107518308227471}}</ref>\n\nAt least up to {{Convert|-173|C|F}}, iron(II) hydride is predicted to have a body-centred tetragonal crystalline structure with the I4/mmm space group. In this structure, iron centres have a capped square-antiprismatic coordination geometry, and hydrogen centres have square-planar and square-pyramidal geometries.\n\n{|align=\"center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! 9-Coordinate Fe-centre !! 4-Coordinate H-centre !! 5-Coordinate H-centre\n|-\n| [[File:Nonahydridorhenate-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]] || [[File:Square-planar-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]] || [[File:Square-pyramidal-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]]\n|}\nAn amorphous form of iron(II) hydride is also known.<ref name=\"Morris2014\" />\n\nThe infrared spectrum for dihydridoiron shows that the molecule has a linear H\u2212Fe\u2212H structure in the gas phase, with an equilibrium distance between the iron atom and the hydrogen atoms of 0.1665&nbsp;nm.<ref name=Koersgen/>\n\n=== Electronic properties ===\n\n{| align=\"right\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ State transitions of <sup>56</sup>FeH<sub>2</sub> in the \u03bd<sub>3</sub> fundamental band<ref name=Koersgen/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n! align=\"left\" | Transition\n! align=\"right\" | Wavenumber<br />(cm<sup>\u22121</sup>)\n! align=\"right\" | Frequency<br />(THz)\n|-\n| P<sub>4</sub>(10)\n| align=\"right\" | 1614.912\n| align=\"right\" | 48.4100\n|-\n| P<sub>4</sub>(7)\n| align=\"right\" | 1633.519\n| align=\"right\" | 48.9717\n|-\n| Q<sub>4</sub>(4),Q<sub>3</sub>(3)\n| align=\"right\" | 1672.658\n| align=\"right\" | 50.1450\n|-\n| Q<sub>4</sub>(4),Q<sub>4</sub>(5),Q<sub>3</sub>(3)\n| align=\"right\" | 1676.183\n| align=\"right\" | 50.2507\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(4)\n| align=\"right\" | 1704.131\n| align=\"right\" | 51.0886\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(5)\n| align=\"right\" | 1707.892\n| align=\"right\" | 51.2013\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(8)\n| align=\"right\" | 1725.227\n| align=\"right\" | 51.7210\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(9)\n| align=\"right\" | 1729.056\n| align=\"right\" | 52.8358\n|}\n\nA few of dihydridoiron's electronic states lie relatively close to each other, giving rise to varying degrees of radical chemistry. The ground state and the first two excited states are all quintet radicals with four [[unpaired electron]]s (''X''<sup>5</sup>\u0394<sub>''g''</sub>, ''A''<sup>5</sup>\u03a0<sub>''g''</sub>, ''B''<sup>5</sup>\u03a3<sub>''g''</sub><sup>+</sup>). With the first two excited states only 22 and 32 kJ&nbsp;mol<sup>\u22121</sup> above the ground state, a sample of dihydridoiron contains trace quantities of excited states even at room temperature. Furthermore, [[Crystal field theory]] predicts that the low transition energies correspond to a colourless compound.\n\nThe ground electronic state is [[molecular term symbol|<sup>5</sup><big>\u0394</big><sub>g</sub>]].<ref name=Koersgen/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Metallurgical chemistry ===\n\nIn iron-hydrogen alloys that have hydrogen content near 3.48 wt%, hydrogen can precipitate as iron(II) hydride and lesser quantities of other polymeric iron hydrides.<ref name=\"Cui2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Cui|first1=Yanguang|last2=Xie|first2=Dongyue|last3=Yu|first3=Ping|last4=Guo|first4=Yunlong|last5=Rong|first5=Yonghua|last6=Zhu|first6=Guozhen|last7=Wen|first7=Mao|date=January 2018|title=Formation of iron hydride in \u03b1-Fe under dislocation strain field and its effect on dislocation interaction|url=https://reader.elsevier.com/reader/sd/E1A6ADD29042A964DAA81FDA8F576FB7CB9E195A75C88ADF0B4B966EE4DD16A2E0A925B33B5D66ACEF5A15FE4C247764|journal=[[Computational Materials Science (journal)|Computational Materials Science]]|volume=141|pages=254\u2013259|doi=10.1016/j.commatsci.2017.09.032|url-access=<!--free-->|via=ScienceDirect}}{{open access}}</ref> However, due to the limited solubility of hydrogen in iron, the optimum content for the formation of iron(II) hydride can only be reached by applying extreme pressure.\n\nIn metallurgical chemistry, iron(II) hydride is fundamental to certain forms of iron-hydrogen alloys. It occurs as a brittle component within the solid matrix, with a physical makeup that depends on its formation conditions and subsequent heat treatment. As it decomposes over time, the alloy will slowly become softer and more ductile, and may start to suffer from [[hydrogen embrittlement]].<ref name=\"Cui2018\" />\n\n== Production ==\n\nDihydridoiron has been produced by several means, including:\n* By reaction of {{chem|FeCl|2}} and PhMgBr under a hydrogen atmosphere (1929).{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n* Electrical discharge in a mixture of [[iron pentacarbonyl|pentacarbonyliron]] and dihydrogen diluted in helium at 8.5 [[Torr]].<ref name=Koersgen/> \n* Evaporation of iron with a [[laser]] in an atmosphere of hydrogen, pure or diluted in [[neon]] or argon, and condensing the products on a cold surface below 10 K.<ref name=Wang2009/><ref name=Chertihin/>  \n* Decomposition product of collision-excited [[ferrocenium]] ions.<ref name=\"Mason2012\">{{cite journal|author1=Rod S. Mason|author2=Lara J. Kelly|title=Synthesis of protonated ferrocene isomers in the gas phase and their study by mass spectrometry|journal=Arkivoc|date=20 August 2012|volume=2012|issue=7|pages=137\u2013157|doi=10.3998/ark.5550190.0013.709|url=http://www.arkat-usa.org/get-file/45359/}}{{Open access}}</ref>\n\n=== Iron reduction ===\n\nMost iron(II) hydride is produced by iron reduction. In this process, stoichiometric amounts of iron and hydrogen react under an applied pressure of between approximately 45 and 75 GPa to produce iron(II) hydride according to the reaction:\n:''n''Fe + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\nThe process involves iron(I) hydride as an intermediate, and occurs in two steps.\n#2''n''Fe + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH)|''n''}}\n#{{Chem|2(FeH)|''n''}} + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\n\n=== Bis[bis(mesityl)iron] reduction ===\n\nAmorphous iron(II) hydride is produced by bis[bis(mesityl)iron] reduction. In this process, bis[bis(mesityl)iron] is reduced with hydrogen under an applied pressure of 100 atmospheres to produce iron(II) hydride according to the reaction:\n:''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|[Fe(mes)|2|]|2}} + 4''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH|2|)|''n''}} + 4''n''&nbsp;Hmes\nThe process involves bis[hydrido(mesityl)iron] and dihydridoiron as intermediates, and occurs in three steps.\n#{{Chem|[Fe(mes)|2|]|2}} + {{Chem|2H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|[FeH(mes)]|2}} + 2&nbsp;Hmes\n#{{Chem|[FeH(mes)]|2}} + {{Chem|H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|FeH|2}} + Hmes\n#''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|FeH|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nAs dihydridoiron is an electron-deficient molecule, it spontaneously autopolymerises in its pure form, or converts to an adduct upon treatment with a Lewis base. Upon treatment of adducts of weak-field Lewis bases with a dilute standard acid, it converts to an hydridoiron(1+) salt and [[hydrogen|elemental hydrogen]]. Treatment of adducts of strong-field Lewis bases with a standard base, converts it to a metal ferrate(1\u2212) salt and water. Oxidation of iron dihydrides give iron(II) hydroxide, whereas reduction gives hexahydridoferrate(4\u2212) salts. Unless cooled to at most{{Convert|\u2212243|C|F}}, dihydridoiron decomposes to produce [[iron|elemental iron]] and hydrogen.<ref name=\"Chertihin\">{{cite journal|author1=George V. Chertihin|author2=Lester Andrews|year=1995|title=Infrared spectra of FeH, {{chem|FeH|2}}, and {{chem|FeH|3}} in solid argo| journal=[[Journal of Physical Chemistry]]|volume=99|issue=32|pages=12131\u201312134|doi=10.1021/j100032a013}}{{Closed access}}</ref> Other iron dihydrides and adducts of dihydridoiron decompose at higher temperatures to also produce elemental hydrogen, and iron or polynuclear iron adducts:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} \u2192 Fe + {{Chem|H|2}}\n[[Non-metals]], including [[oxygen]], strongly attack iron dihydrides, forming hydrogenated compounds and iron(II) compounds:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|O|2}} \u2192 FeO + {{Chem|H|2|O}}\nIron(II) compounds can also be prepared from an iron dihydride and an appropriate, concentrated acid:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + 2&nbsp;HCl \u2192 {{Chem|FeCl|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}}\n\n== History ==\n\nEven though complexes containing dihydridoiron was known since 1931,<ref name=\"Hieber1931\">{{Cite journal|last=Hieber|first=W.|author2=Leutert, F.|date=1 April 1931|title=Zur kenntnis des koordinativ gebundenen kohlenoxyds: Bildung von eisencarbonylwasserstoff|trans-title=For the knowledge of the coordinatively bound carbon monoxide: Formation of iron carbonyl hydrogen<!--via Google Translate-->|journal=[[Naturwissenschaften]]|language=German|volume=19|issue=17|pages=360\u2013361|bibcode=1931NW.....19..360H|doi=10.1007/BF01522286|issn=1432-1904}}\n</ref> the simple compound with the molecular formula {{Chem|FeH|2}} is only a much more recent discovery. Following the discovery of the first complex containing dihydridoiron, [[iron tetracarbonyl hydride|tetracarbonylate]], it was also quickly discovered that it is not possible to remove the carbon monoxide by thermal means - heating an dihydridoiron containing complex only causes it to decompose, a habit attributable to the weak iron-hydrogen bond. Thus, a practical method has been sought since then for the production of the pure compound, without the involvement of a liquid phase. Furthermore, there is also on going research into its other adducts. Although iron(II) hydride has received attention only recently, complexes containing the dihydridoiron group have been known at least since 1931, when [[iron carbonyl hydride]] FeH<sub>2</sub>(CO)<sub>4</sub> was first synthesised.<ref name=Hieber1931 /> The most precisely characterised FeH<sub>2</sub>L<sub>4</sub> complex as of 2003 is FeH<sub>2</sub>(CO)<sub>2</sub>[P(OPh)<sub>3</sub>]<sub>2</sub>.\n\nComplexes can also contain FeH<sub>2</sub> with hydrogen molecules as a ligand.  Those with one or two molecules of hydrogen are unstable, but FeH<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>)<sub>3</sub> is stable and can be produced by the evaporation of iron into hydrogen gas.<ref name=\"Wang2009\">{{cite journal|last=Wang|first=Xuefeng|author2=Lester Andrews|date=18 December 2008|title=Infrared Spectra and Theoretical Calculations for Fe, Ru, and Os Metal Hydrides and Dihydrogen Complexes|journal=[[J. Phys. Chem. A|The Journal of Physical Chemistry A]]|volume=113|issue=3|pages=551\u2013563|doi=10.1021/jp806845h|pmid=19099441|issn=1089-5639}}</ref>\n\nFrom infrared spectra of samples of dihydridoiron trapped in frozen argon between 10 and 30 K, Chertihin and Andrews conjectured in 1995 that dihydridoiron readily [[dimer (chemistry)|dimerized]] into {{chem|Fe|2|H|4}}, and that it reacts with atomic hydrogen to produce trihydridoiron ({{chem|FeH|3}}).<ref name=Chertihin/> However, it was later proven that the product of the reaction was likely to have been hydrido(dihydrogen)iron ({{Chem|FeH(H|2|)}}).<ref name=Wang2009/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Iron compounds}}\n{{Hydrides by group}}\n\n[[Category:Iron(II) compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal hydrides]]\n", "text_old": "{{chembox\n| Name = Iron(II) hydride\n| SystematicName = Dihydridoiron(4\u2022)\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo = 33485-98-2\n| CASNo_Ref = \n| PubChem = 141155\n\n| SMILES = [FeH2]\n| ChemSpiderID = 124509\n| StdInChI = 1S/Fe.2H\n| StdInChIKey = FUEZNWLRTWZOHC-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = FeH<sub>2</sub><sup>4\u2022</sup>\n| MolarMass = 57.861 g mol<sup>\u22121</sup>\n}}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherCompounds = [[iron hydride]]s, [[Iron(I) hydride|FeH]], [[FeH3]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Iron(II) hydride''', systematically named '''iron dihydride''' and '''poly(dihydridoiron)''' is solid [[inorganic compound]] with the [[chemical formula]] {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}} (also written {{Chem|([FeH|2|]}})<sub>''n''</sub> or {{Chem|FeH|2}}). ). It is kinetically unstable at ambient temperature, and as such, little is known about its bulk properties. However, it known as a black, amorphous powder, which was synthesised for the first time in 2014.<ref name=\"Morris2014\">{{Cite journal|last1=Morris|first1=Leah|last2=Trudeau|first2=Michel L.|last3=Lees|first3=Martin R.|last4=Hanna|first4=John V.|last5=Antonelli|first5=David M.|date=25 March 2014|title=On the path to bulk {{Chem|FeH|2}}: Synthesis and magnetic properties of amorphous iron(II) hydride|journal=Journal of Alloys and Compounds|volume=590|pages=199\u2013204|doi=10.1016/j.jallcom.2013.12.099}}</ref>\n\nIron(II) hydride is the second simplest polymeric iron hydride (after [[iron(I) hydride]]). Due to its instability, it has no practical industrial uses. However, in [[metallurgy|metallurgical]] chemistry, iron(II) hydride is fundamental to certain forms of [[iron-hydrogen alloy]]s.\n\n== Nomenclature ==\n\nThe systematic name ''iron dihydride'', a valid [[IUPAC]] name, is constructed according to the compositional nomenclature. However, as the name is compositional in nature, it does not distinguish between compounds of the same stoichiometry, such as molecular species, which exhibit distinct chemical properties. The systematic names ''poly(dihydridoiron)'' and ''poly[ferrane(2)]'', also valid IUPAC names, are constructed according to the additive and electron-deficient substitutive nomenclatures, respectively. They do distinguish the titular compound from the others.\n\n== Dihydridoiron ==\n\n[[File:Linear-3D-balls.png|150px|thumb|right]]\nDihydridoiron, also systematically named ferrane(2), is a related inorganic compound with the chemical formula {{Chem|FeH|2}} (also written {{Chem|[FeH|2|]}}). It is both kinetically unstable at concentration and at ambient temperature.\n\nDihydridoiron is the second simplest molecular iron hydride (after hydridoiron), and is also the progenitor of clusters with the same stoichiometry. In addition, it may be considered to be the iron(II) hydride monomer.\n\nIt has been observed in [[matrix isolation]].<ref name=\"Koersgen\">Helga K\u00f6rsgen, Petra M\u00fcrtz, Klaus Lipus, Wolfgang Urban, Jonathan P. Towle, John M. Brown (1996), \"[https://aip.scitation.org/doi/pdf/10.1063/1.471180 The identification of the {{chem|FeH|2}} radical in the gas phase by infrared spectroscopy]\".{{Closed access}} [[J. Chem. Phys.|The Journal of Chemical Physics]], volume 104, issue 12, page 4859 {{ISSN|0021-9606}} {{doi|10.1063/1.471180}}\n</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\n\n=== Acidity and basicity ===\n\nAn electron pair of a Lewis base can join with the iron centre in dihydridoiron by adduction:\n:{{Chem|[FeH|2|]}} + :L \u2192 {{Chem|[FeH|2|L]}}\nBecause of this capture of an adducted [[electron pair]], dihydridoiron has Lewis acidic character. Dihydridoiron has the capacity to capture up to four electron pairs from Lewis bases.\n\nA proton can join with the iron centre by dissociative protonation:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|H|+}} \u2192 {{Chem|FeH|+}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nBecause dissociative protonation involves the capture of the [[proton]] ({{Chem|H|+}}) to form a Kubas complex ({{Chem|[FeH(H|2|)}}]<sup>+</sup>) as an intermediate, dihydridoiron and its adducts of weak-field Lewis bases, such as water, also have Br\u00f8nsted\u2013Lowry basic character. They have the capacity to capture up to two protons. Its dissociated [[conjugate acid]]s are hydridoiron(1+) and iron(2+) ({{Chem|FeH|+}} and {{Chem|Fe|2+}}).\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}} {{Eqm}} {{Chem|FeH|+}} + {{Chem|H|2|O}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nAqueous solutions of adducts of weak-field Lewis bases are however, unstable due to hydrolysis of the dihydridoiron and hydridoiron(1+) groups:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2|O}} \u2192 {{Chem|Fe(OH)|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}}\n:{{Chem|FeH|+}} + 3&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2|O}} \u2192 {{Chem|Fe(OH)|2}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}} + {{Chem|H|2}}\nIt should be expected that iron dihydride clusters and iron(II) hydride have similar acid-base properties, although reaction rates and equilibrium constants are different.\n\nAlternatively, a hydrogen centre in the dihydridoiron group in adducts of strong-field Lewis bases, such as carbon monoxide, may separate from the molecule by ionisation:\n:{{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H|2|]}} \u2192 {{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H]|-}} + {{Chem|H|+}}\nBecause of this release of the proton, adducts of strong-field Lewis bases have may have Br\u00f8nsted\u2013Lowry acidic character. They have the capacity to release up to two protons.\n:{{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H|2|]}} +{{Chem|H|2|O}} {{Eqm}} {{Chem|[Fe(CO)|4|H]|-}} + {{Chem|H|3|O|+}}\nMixed adducts with Lewis bases of differing fields strengths may exhibit intermediate behaviour.<ref name=\"Basallote1998\">{{cite journal|last1=Basallote|first1=Manuel G.|last2=Dur\u00e1n|first2=Joaqu\u00edn|last3=Fern\u00e1ndez-Trujillo|first3=M. Jes\u00fas|last4=M\u00e1\u00f1ez|first4=M. Angeles|date=1998|title=Kinetics of protonation of ''cis''-[{{Chem|FeH|2}}(dppe){{sub|2}}]: Formation of the dihydrogen complex ''trans''-[{{Chem|[FeH(H|2|)}}(dppe){{sub|2}}]+ (dppe = {{Chem|Ph|2|PCH|2|CH|2|PPh|2}})|journal=[[Dalton Trans.|Journal of the Chemical Society, Dalton Transactions]]|volume=0|issue=13|pages=2205\u20132210|doi=10.1039/A800916C}}</ref>\n\n=== Structure ===\n\nIn iron(II) hydride, the atoms form a network, individual atoms being interconnected by [[covalent bond]]s. Since it is a polymeric solid, a monocrystalline sample is not expected to undergo state transitions, such as melting and dissolution, as this would require the rearrangement of molecular bonds and consequently, change its chemical identity. Colloidal crystalline samples, wherein intermolecular forces are relevant, are expected to undergo state transitions.<ref name=\"Pieranski2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Pieranski|first1=Pawel|date=20 August 2006|title=Colloidal crystals|journal=[[Contemp. Phys.|Contemporary Physics]]|volume=24|issue=1|pages=25\u201373|doi=10.1080/00107518308227471}}</ref>\n\nAt least up to {{Convert|-173|C|F}}, iron(II) hydride is predicted to have a body-centred tetragonal crystalline structure with the I4/mmm space group. In this structure, iron centres have a capped square-antiprismatic coordination geometry, and hydrogen centres have square-planar and square-pyramidal geometries.\n\n{|align=\"center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! 9-Coordinate Fe-centre !! 4-Coordinate H-centre !! 5-Coordinate H-centre\n|-\n| [[File:Nonahydridorhenate-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]] || [[File:Square-planar-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]] || [[File:Square-pyramidal-3D-balls.png|100px|frameless|center]]\n|}\nAn amorphous form of iron(II) hydride is also known.<ref name=\"Morris2014\" />\n\nThe infrared spectrum for dihydridoiron shows that the molecule has a linear H\u2212Fe\u2212H structure in the gas phase, with an equilibrium distance between the iron atom and the hydrogen atoms of 0.1665&nbsp;nm.<ref name=Koersgen/>\n\n=== Electronic properties ===\n\n{| align=\"right\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ State transitions of <sup>56</sup>FeH<sub>2</sub> in the \u03bd<sub>3</sub> fundamental band<ref name=Koersgen/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n! align=\"left\" | Transition\n! align=\"right\" | Wavenumber<br />(cm<sup>\u22121</sup>)\n! align=\"right\" | Frequency<br />(THz)\n|-\n| P<sub>4</sub>(10)\n| align=\"right\" | 1614.912\n| align=\"right\" | 48.4100\n|-\n| P<sub>4</sub>(7)\n| align=\"right\" | 1633.519\n| align=\"right\" | 48.9717\n|-\n| Q<sub>4</sub>(4),Q<sub>3</sub>(3)\n| align=\"right\" | 1672.658\n| align=\"right\" | 50.1450\n|-\n| Q<sub>4</sub>(4),Q<sub>4</sub>(5),Q<sub>3</sub>(3)\n| align=\"right\" | 1676.183\n| align=\"right\" | 50.2507\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(4)\n| align=\"right\" | 1704.131\n| align=\"right\" | 51.0886\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(5)\n| align=\"right\" | 1707.892\n| align=\"right\" | 51.2013\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(8)\n| align=\"right\" | 1725.227\n| align=\"right\" | 51.7210\n|-\n| R<sub>4</sub>(9)\n| align=\"right\" | 1729.056\n| align=\"right\" | 52.8358\n|}\n\nA few of dihydridoiron's electronic states lie relatively close to each other, giving rise to varying degrees of radical chemistry. The ground state and the first two excited states are all quintet radicals with four [[unpaired electron]]s (''X''<sup>5</sup>\u0394<sub>''g''</sub>, ''A''<sup>5</sup>\u03a0<sub>''g''</sub>, ''B''<sup>5</sup>\u03a3<sub>''g''</sub><sup>+</sup>). With the first two excited states only 22 and 32 kJ&nbsp;mol<sup>\u22121</sup> above the ground state, a sample of dihydridoiron contains trace quantities of excited states even at room temperature. Furthermore, [[Crystal field theory]] predicts that the low transition energies correspond to a colourless compound.\n\nThe ground electronic state is [[molecular term symbol|<sup>5</sup><big>\u0394</big><sub>g</sub>]].<ref name=Koersgen/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Metallurgical chemistry ===\n\nIn iron-hydrogen alloys that have hydrogen content near 3.48 wt%, hydrogen can precipitate as iron(II) hydride and lesser quantities of other polymeric iron hydrides.<ref name=\"Cui2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Cui|first1=Yanguang|last2=Xie|first2=Dongyue|last3=Yu|first3=Ping|last4=Guo|first4=Yunlong|last5=Rong|first5=Yonghua|last6=Zhu|first6=Guozhen|last7=Wen|first7=Mao|date=January 2018|title=Formation of iron hydride in \u03b1-Fe under dislocation strain field and its effect on dislocation interaction|url=https://reader.elsevier.com/reader/sd/E1A6ADD29042A964DAA81FDA8F576FB7CB9E195A75C88ADF0B4B966EE4DD16A2E0A925B33B5D66ACEF5A15FE4C247764|journal=[[Comput. Mater. Sci.|Computational Materials Science]]|volume=141|pages=254\u2013259|doi=10.1016/j.commatsci.2017.09.032|url-access=<!--free-->|via=ScienceDirect}}{{open access}}</ref> However, due to the limited solubility of hydrogen in iron, the optimum content for the formation of iron(II) hydride can only be reached by applying extreme pressure.\n\nIn metallurgical chemistry, iron(II) hydride is fundamental to certain forms of iron-hydrogen alloys. It occurs as a brittle component within the solid matrix, with a physical makeup that depends on its formation conditions and subsequent heat treatment. As it decomposes over time, the alloy will slowly become softer and more ductile, and may start to suffer from [[hydrogen embrittlement]].<ref name=\"Cui2018\" />\n\n== Production ==\n\nDihydridoiron has been produced by several means, including:\n* By reaction of {{chem|FeCl|2}} and PhMgBr under a hydrogen atmosphere (1929).{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n* Electrical discharge in a mixture of [[iron pentacarbonyl|pentacarbonyliron]] and dihydrogen diluted in helium at 8.5 [[Torr]].<ref name=Koersgen/> \n* Evaporation of iron with a [[laser]] in an atmosphere of hydrogen, pure or diluted in [[neon]] or argon, and condensing the products on a cold surface below 10 K.<ref name=Wang2009/><ref name=Chertihin/>  \n* Decomposition product of collision-excited [[ferrocenium]] ions.<ref name=\"Mason2012\">{{cite journal|author1=Rod S. Mason|author2=Lara J. Kelly|title=Synthesis of protonated ferrocene isomers in the gas phase and their study by mass spectrometry|journal=Arkivoc|date=20 August 2012|volume=2012|issue=7|pages=137\u2013157|doi=10.3998/ark.5550190.0013.709|url=http://www.arkat-usa.org/get-file/45359/}}{{Open access}}</ref>\n\n=== Iron reduction ===\n\nMost iron(II) hydride is produced by iron reduction. In this process, stoichiometric amounts of iron and hydrogen react under an applied pressure of between approximately 45 and 75 GPa to produce iron(II) hydride according to the reaction:\n:''n''Fe + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\nThe process involves iron(I) hydride as an intermediate, and occurs in two steps.\n#2''n''Fe + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH)|''n''}}\n#{{Chem|2(FeH)|''n''}} + {{Chem|''n''H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\n\n=== Bis[bis(mesityl)iron] reduction ===\n\nAmorphous iron(II) hydride is produced by bis[bis(mesityl)iron] reduction. In this process, bis[bis(mesityl)iron] is reduced with hydrogen under an applied pressure of 100 atmospheres to produce iron(II) hydride according to the reaction:\n:''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|[Fe(mes)|2|]|2}} + 4''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|2(FeH|2|)|''n''}} + 4''n''&nbsp;Hmes\nThe process involves bis[hydrido(mesityl)iron] and dihydridoiron as intermediates, and occurs in three steps.\n#{{Chem|[Fe(mes)|2|]|2}} + {{Chem|2H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|[FeH(mes)]|2}} + 2&nbsp;Hmes\n#{{Chem|[FeH(mes)]|2}} + {{Chem|H|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|FeH|2}} + Hmes\n#''n''&nbsp;{{Chem|FeH|2}} \u2192 {{Chem|(FeH|2|)|''n''}}\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nAs dihydridoiron is an electron-deficient molecule, it spontaneously autopolymerises in its pure form, or converts to an adduct upon treatment with a Lewis base. Upon treatment of adducts of weak-field Lewis bases with a dilute standard acid, it converts to an hydridoiron(1+) salt and [[hydrogen|elemental hydrogen]]. Treatment of adducts of strong-field Lewis bases with a standard base, converts it to a metal ferrate(1\u2212) salt and water. Oxidation of iron dihydrides give iron(II) hydroxide, whereas reduction gives hexahydridoferrate(4\u2212) salts. Unless cooled to at most{{Convert|\u2212243|C|F}}, dihydridoiron decomposes to produce [[iron|elemental iron]] and hydrogen.<ref name=\"Chertihin\">{{cite journal|author1=George V. Chertihin|author2=Lester Andrews|year=1995|title=Infrared spectra of FeH, {{chem|FeH|2}}, and {{chem|FeH|3}} in solid argo| journal=[[Journal of Physical Chemistry]]|volume=99|issue=32|pages=12131\u201312134|doi=10.1021/j100032a013}}{{Closed access}}</ref> Other iron dihydrides and adducts of dihydridoiron decompose at higher temperatures to also produce elemental hydrogen, and iron or polynuclear iron adducts:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} \u2192 Fe + {{Chem|H|2}}\n[[Non-metals]], including [[oxygen]], strongly attack iron dihydrides, forming hydrogenated compounds and iron(II) compounds:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + {{Chem|O|2}} \u2192 FeO + {{Chem|H|2|O}}\nIron(II) compounds can also be prepared from an iron dihydride and an appropriate, concentrated acid:\n:{{Chem|FeH|2}} + 2&nbsp;HCl \u2192 {{Chem|FeCl|2}} + 2&nbsp;{{Chem|H|2}}\n\n== History ==\n\nEven though complexes containing dihydridoiron was known since 1931,<ref name=\"Hieber1931\">{{Cite journal|last=Hieber|first=W.|author2=Leutert, F.|date=1 April 1931|title=Zur kenntnis des koordinativ gebundenen kohlenoxyds: Bildung von eisencarbonylwasserstoff|trans-title=For the knowledge of the coordinatively bound carbon monoxide: Formation of iron carbonyl hydrogen<!--via Google Translate-->|journal=[[Naturwissenschaften]]|language=German|volume=19|issue=17|pages=360\u2013361|bibcode=1931NW.....19..360H|doi=10.1007/BF01522286|issn=1432-1904}}\n</ref> the simple compound with the molecular formula {{Chem|FeH|2}} is only a much more recent discovery. Following the discovery of the first complex containing dihydridoiron, [[iron tetracarbonyl hydride|tetracarbonylate]], it was also quickly discovered that it is not possible to remove the carbon monoxide by thermal means - heating an dihydridoiron containing complex only causes it to decompose, a habit attributable to the weak iron-hydrogen bond. Thus, a practical method has been sought since then for the production of the pure compound, without the involvement of a liquid phase. Furthermore, there is also on going research into its other adducts. Although iron(II) hydride has received attention only recently, complexes containing the dihydridoiron group have been known at least since 1931, when [[iron carbonyl hydride]] FeH<sub>2</sub>(CO)<sub>4</sub> was first synthesised.<ref name=Hieber1931 /> The most precisely characterised FeH<sub>2</sub>L<sub>4</sub> complex as of 2003 is FeH<sub>2</sub>(CO)<sub>2</sub>[P(OPh)<sub>3</sub>]<sub>2</sub>.\n\nComplexes can also contain FeH<sub>2</sub> with hydrogen molecules as a ligand.  Those with one or two molecules of hydrogen are unstable, but FeH<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>)<sub>3</sub> is stable and can be produced by the evaporation of iron into hydrogen gas.<ref name=\"Wang2009\">{{cite journal|last=Wang|first=Xuefeng|author2=Lester Andrews|date=18 December 2008|title=Infrared Spectra and Theoretical Calculations for Fe, Ru, and Os Metal Hydrides and Dihydrogen Complexes|journal=[[J. Phys. Chem. A|The Journal of Physical Chemistry A]]|volume=113|issue=3|pages=551\u2013563|doi=10.1021/jp806845h|pmid=19099441|issn=1089-5639}}</ref>\n\nFrom infrared spectra of samples of dihydridoiron trapped in frozen argon between 10 and 30 K, Chertihin and Andrews conjectured in 1995 that dihydridoiron readily [[dimer (chemistry)|dimerized]] into {{chem|Fe|2|H|4}}, and that it reacts with atomic hydrogen to produce trihydridoiron ({{chem|FeH|3}}).<ref name=Chertihin/> However, it was later proven that the product of the reaction was likely to have been hydrido(dihydrogen)iron ({{Chem|FeH(H|2|)}}).<ref name=Wang2009/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Iron compounds}}\n{{Hydrides by group}}\n\n[[Category:Iron(II) compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal hydrides]]\n", "name_user": "Nodoru", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Update CMSE link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron(II)_hydride"}
{"title_page": "Hannah Simone", "text_new": "{{Short description|Canadian television host, actress and fashion model}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Hannah Simone\n| image        = Hannah Simone (1) (cropped).jpg \n| caption      = Simone in March 2012\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1980|8|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| home_town    = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| occupation   = Actress, model, television hostess, VJ\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Jesse Giddings]]|2016}}\n| children     = 1\n}}\n\n'''Hannah Simone''' (born August 3, 1980) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] actress, [[Television presenter|television host]], and former [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]] and fashion model. She is best known for portraying [[List of New Girl characters#Cece|Cece]] on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[New Girl]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nSimone was born in London to an [[Indian people|Indian]] father and an English mother of [[German people|German]], [[Italian people|Italian]], and [[Greek Cypriot]] descent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://audreymagazine.com/spring-12-feature-hannah-simone/ |title=Spring \u201912 Feature &#124; Hannah Simone |publisher=Audrey Magazine |date=May 28, 2013 |access-date=November 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629052111/http://audreymagazine.com/spring-12-feature-hannah-simone/ |archive-date=June 29, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She has a brother named Zach.<ref name=\"India.com\">{{cite web|author=Jennifer Chowdhury |url=http://www.india.com/entertainment/9-things-you-didnt-know-about-actress-hannah-simone-224131/ |title=12 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Actress Hannah Simone |publisher=India.com |date= |accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Simone spent her early childhood in [[Calgary]]. From ages 7\u201310, Simone  moved through three continents, attending schools in each one. At the age of 13, Simone was living in [[Cyprus]] and was working as a [[Model (person)|fashion model]]. At 16 years old, Simone lived in [[New Delhi]] where she attended the American Embassy School. A year later, at 17, she returned to Canada. Initially settling at [[White Rock, British Columbia]], she subsequently relocated to [[Vancouver]]<ref name=\"mmprofile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.muchmusic.com/tv/personalities/hannahsimone/ |title=MuchMusic Personalities&nbsp;\u2014 Hannah Simone |access-date=December 17, 2009 |publisher= MuchMusic |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525061500/http://www.muchmusic.com/tv/personalities/hannahsimone/ |archive-date=May 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> where she attended the [[University of British Columbia]]. After her first degree, she returned to the United Kingdom, Hounslow for a year, where she worked as a human rights and refugees officer.<ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WLynlG2QJxM|title=Hannah Simone Chats about Dating & Life Before New Girl - Girl Crush|first=|last=SheKnows|date=July 25, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=November 12, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing her 2005 graduation from [[Ryerson University]], Simone became host of [[HGTV Canada]]'s television show ''Space for Living'' for its first season.<ref>[http://www.ryerson.ca/fcad/news/2005.html Ryerson Faculty of Communication and Design: 2005 announcements] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516205957/http://www.ryerson.ca/fcad/news/2005.html |date=May 16, 2006 }} (\"Space for Living co-hosted by RTA Grad Hannah Simone\")</ref>\n\nSimone worked at [[MuchMusic]] as a VJ at MuchMusic Headquarters, as a [[news presenter]] for \"Much News Weekly\" and, the host of the show ''[[The NewMusic]]''. From May 2006 to November 2008, she worked as a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]] for [[MuchMusic]] in [[Canada]]. She related well to youth interested in alternative artists and interviewed many artists and bands during her time at Much. Simone stopped working at MuchMusic on November 21, 2008, stating that she had plans to move to Los Angeles, California.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nSimone earned a role hosting ''[[WCG Ultimate Gamer]]'' alongside Joel Gourdin on [[Syfy]].<ref name=\"wcg\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/943/943181p1.html |title=Hosts Picked for Cable Game-Off |accessdate=December 17, 2009 |publisher=IGN}}</ref><ref name=\"wcg2\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/951/951488p1.html |title=IGN Exclusive&nbsp;\u2013 ''WCG Ultimate Gamer'' Webisode&nbsp;\u2013 Preview |accessdate=December 17, 2009 |publisher=IGN}}</ref> The series premiered on March 10, 2009 and ended after its second season on October 7, 2010. From 2011 to 2018, Simone starred on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox's]] comedy ''[[New Girl]]'', where she played [[Cece (New Girl)|Cece]], the best friend to title character Jess ([[Zooey Deschanel]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/fox-picks-up-alcatraz-finder-and-new-girl-to-series.html |title=FOX picks up 'Alcatraz,' 'The Finder' and 'The New Girl' to series. |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=May 22, 2011 |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514164418/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/fox-picks-up-alcatraz-finder-and-new-girl-to-series.html |archive-date=May 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAlongside [[Kate Upton]] and [[G\u00e9nesis Rodr\u00edguez]], she was featured in [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette\u2019s]] \"What Women Want\" campaign in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lanford|last=Beard|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/04/10/new-girl-hannah-simone-bachelorette-party/ |title='New Girl': Hannah Simone on 'Bachelorette Party,' Cece's 'wild and crazy' season finale |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 10, 2013 |accessdate=September 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she starred alongside [[Danny Trejo]] in [[Train (band)|Train]]'s music video \"[[Angel in Blue Jeans]]\".<ref name=\"angel\"/>\n\nIn 2016, she starred in music video \"Same Air\" from [[The Rocket Summer]]. In 2017, she hosted the 8-episode first season of the reality competition television series ''[[Kicking & Screaming (TV series)|Kicking & Screaming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hannah Simone to Host New Survival Competition Series \"Kicking & Screaming\"|url=http://www.fox.com/kicking-screaming/article/hannah-simone-to-host-new-survival-competition-series-%E2%80%9Ckicking-screaming%E2%80%9D%C2%A0|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]]|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2018, Simone was announced as the lead in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s reboot of ''[[The Greatest American Hero]]'';<ref name= \"reboot\">{{cite news |last=Snierson |first=Dan |url= http://ew.com/tv/2018/02/12/hannah-simone-greatest-american-hero-reboot/ |title=''New Girl'' star Hannah Simone to headline ABC's ''Greatest American Hero'' reboot |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 12, 2018 |accessdate=February 13, 2018}}</ref> however, ABC declined to pick up the series.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=The 5 Most Surprising Pilot Passes This Season|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/5-surprising-pilot-passes-season-1111291|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSimone married musician [[Jesse Giddings]] in 2016, after nearly four years of dating. Simone announced her pregnancy in April 2017, and she gave birth to their son in early August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|first=Karen|last=Mizoguchi|url=http://people.com/babies/hannah-simone-pregnant-expecting-first-child-jesse-giddings-married/|title=Hannah Simone and Jesse Giddings Are Married, Expecting First Child|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 14, 2017|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Yvonne|last1=Juris|first2=Alexia|last2=Fernandez| url=http://people.com/babies/hannah-simone-husband-jesse-giddings-welcome-son/|title=New Girl Hannah Simone and Jesse Giddings Welcome Their First Baby!|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=August 31, 2017|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Sati Shaves Her Head''\n| Nikki\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Oldboy (2013 film)|Oldboy]]''\n| Stephanie Lee\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Miss India America''\n| Sonia Nielson\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Lemonade''\n| Tasha\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Flock of Dudes]]''\n| Beth\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Folk Hero & Funny Guy]]''\n| Emily\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Odd Squad]]: The Movie''\n| Weird Emily\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Band Aid (film)|Band Aid]]''\n| Grace\n|\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Killing Gunther]]''\n|Sanaa\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Kevin Hill]]''\n| Larissa\n| Episode: \"Only Sixteen\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Kojak (2005 TV series)|Kojak]]''\n| Sexy Girl\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Beautiful People (U.S. TV series)|Beautiful People]]''\n| Customer Fix Caf\u00e9\n| Episode: \"A Tale of Two Parties\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132010\n| ''[[WCG Ultimate Gamer]]''\n| Host\n| 2 seasons<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZtzPuIrMuw|title=WCG ultimate Gamer Season I : First Episode|first=|last=WorldCyberGames|date=January 6, 2010|publisher=|accessdate=November 12, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\u20132018\n| ''[[New Girl]]''\n| [[List of New Girl characters#Cece|Cece]]\n| Starring role; 7 seasons<br/>[[Teen Choice Awards]] Choice TV Breakout Performance&nbsp;\u2014 Female\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[H+: The Digital Series]]''\n