ian descent]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Much (TV channel) personalities]]\n[[Category:People from White Rock, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Ryerson University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rogerjdsilva", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hannah_Simone"}
{"title_page": "Maryland Renaissance Festival", "text_new": "{{short description|Located in Crownsville, Maryland}}\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name = Maryland Renaissance Festival\n|image = 2019 Maryland Renaissance Festival 4.jpg\n|alt = \n|caption = Crowds watch a [[Shakespearean]] play at the festival\n|location = [[Crownsville, Maryland|Crownsville]], [[Maryland]]\n|genre = Renaissance fair\n|first = 1977\n|dates = August \u2013 October\n|attendance = 15,800 daily, 300,000 season (average)\n|area = {{convert|25|acre|m2}}\n|free_label = Stages\n|free_text = 10\n|website = {{url|http://www.MarylandRenaissanceFestival.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Maryland Renaissance Festival''' is a [[Renaissance fair]] located in [[Crownsville, Maryland|Crownsville]], [[Maryland]]. Set in a fictional 16th-century English village named ''Revel Grove'', the festival is spread over {{convert|27|acre|m2}}.<ref name=\"baltimoresun2018\"/> The second largest renaissance fair in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwood|first=Arin|title=Maryland Renaissance Festival 2012: Cheesecake On A Stick, Costumes, Catapult Demonstrations|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/25/maryland-renaissance-festival_n_1912993.html|accessdate=20 July 2013|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=2012-09-25}}</ref> it is open from the last weekend of August and runs for nine weekends.\n\n== History ==\n\nIn early 1970s, Minnesota lawyer Jules Smith Sr. (1930\u20132018) invested in Coluam's Minneapolis festival, which later become [[Texas Renaissance Festival]]. When Coluam's Minneapolis festival moved to Texas, Smith sold his shares and organized similar festival in Maryland, nearby [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] in Columbia. The fair was first held for four weekends in 1977 and drew 17 thousand people to see performances by [[Penn and Teller]] and [[The Flying Karamazov Brothers]] among other.<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite book|last=Korol-Evans|first=Kimberly Tony|title=Renaissance Festivals: Merrying the Past and Present|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|pages=25\u201326|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RseqsimMHGEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA26#v=onepage}}</ref> In 1985, the fair was moved to its current location in Crownsville and in 1986 Smith turned over the management of the fair to his son Jules Smith Jr. who still runs the festival with three siblings.<ref name=\"evans\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Felice |first1=Selene San |title=Renaissance Festival co-founder Jules Smith Sr. dies at 88 |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/obituaries/ac-cn-jules-smith-0911-story.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=capitalgazette.com |publisher=[[Capital Gazette]] |date=10 September 2018}}</ref> The festival was originally an Elizabethan fair, but in 1989 switched to being focused on [[Henry VIII of England]].<ref name=\"evans\" /> King Henry is played by actor Fred Nelson, replacing [[Bill Huttel]], after Huttel's death in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Amanda|title=Fred Nelson - King Henry VIII at Maryland Renaissance Festival, Crownsville|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/magazine/2003/10/19/fred-nelson-king-henry-viii-at-maryland-renaissance-festival-crownsville/b98ca2e1-ddbb-435f-9db7-84d1df751dfc/|website=Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=20 February 2018|date=19 October 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Fair==\n[[File:Maryland Renaissance Festival 2.jpg|thumb|left| [[Theatrical jousting|Jousting]] at the Renaissance Festival]]\nThe [[Tudor style architecture|English Tudor]] village is {{convert|27|acre|m2}}<ref name=\"baltimoresun2018\">{{cite news |last1=Britto |first1=Brittany |title=15 things you're bound to see at the Maryland Renaissance Festival |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-sights-maryland-rennfest-photogallery.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=baltimoresun.com |publisher=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=2018}}</ref> of woods and fields. There are more than 130 [[craft]] shops and 42 food outlets.\n\nMore than 1,300 participants populate the village, 400 work directly for the company, 700 for the other vendors and 200 as performers<ref name=\"capitalgazette2018\">{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |title=Maryland Renaissance Festival: Setting the historical record straight |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/entertainment/ac-en-rennfest-0817-story.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=capitalgazette.com |publisher=[[Capital Gazette]] |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> on stages or as characters throughout the village. The Maryland Renaissance Festival utilizes eight major theaters, four smaller stages in taverns, a children's area and a jousting tiltyard with seating for 3,000.\n\nThe fair contains an elephant and camel that groups of fairgoers pay to ride. The provider of the elephant, Frank Murray, was charged with four counts of cruelty to animals and paid about $3,000 in fines in 2011 <ref>{{cite web|title=The elephant in the room: Controversial animal rides stay at Maryland Renaissance Festival|url=https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/ac-cn-elephant-20171022-story.html|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>. In 2014, [[Joan Jett]], speaking on behalf of [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]], wrote a letter asking that the rides be cancelled because of exploitation and abuse associated with using animals in this fashion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joan Jett Urges Maryland Renaissance Festival to End Elephant Rides|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/12659-joan-jett-urges-maryland-renaissance-festival-to-end-elephant-rides|accessdate=10 October 2014|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Born Free USA also protested on a road outside the fair.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gillespie|first1=Paul W.|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/multimedia/photos/cg-maryland-renaissance-festival-opens-picture-015,0,5827027.photo|title=Maryland Renaissance Festival|website=Capital Gazette|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Renaissance fairs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.rennfest.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Coord|39|00|06|N|76|35|01|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark_scale:3000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Festivals in Maryland|Renaissance Festival]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Renaissance fairs]]\n[[Category:Festivals established in 1977]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Located in Crownsville, Maryland}}\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name = Maryland Renaissance Festival\n|image = 2019 Maryland Renaissance Festival 4.jpg\n|alt = \n|caption = Crowds watch a [[Shakespearean]] play at the festival\n|location = [[Crownsville, Maryland|Crownsville]], [[Maryland]]\n|genre = Renaissance fair\n|first = 1977\n|dates = August \u2013 October\n|attendance = 15,800 daily, 300,000 season (average)\n|area = {{convert|25|acre|m2}}\n|free_label = Stages\n|free_text = 10\n|website = {{url|http://www.MarylandRenaissanceFestival.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Maryland Renaissance Festival''' is a [[Renaissance fair]] located in [[Crownsville, Maryland|Crownsville]], [[Maryland]]. Set in a fictional 16th-century English village named ''Revel Grove'', the festival is spread over {{convert|27|acre|m2}}.<ref name=\"baltimoresun2018\"/> The second largest renaissance fair in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwood|first=Arin|title=Maryland Renaissance Festival 2012: Cheesecake On A Stick, Costumes, Catapult Demonstrations|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/25/maryland-renaissance-festival_n_1912993.html|accessdate=20 July 2013|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=2012-09-25}}</ref> it is open from the last weekend of August and runs for nine weekends.\n\n== History ==\n\nIn early 1970s, Minnesota lawyer Jules Smith Sr. (1930\u20132018) invested in Coluam's Minneapolis festival, which later become [[Texas Renaissance Festival]]. When Coluam's Minneapolis festival moved to Texas, Smith sold his shares and organized similar festival in Maryland, nearby [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]] in Columbia. The fair was first held for four weekends in 1977 and drew 17 thousand people to see performances by [[Penn and Teller]] and [[The Flying Karamazov Brothers]] among other.<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite book|last=Korol-Evans|first=Kimberly Tony|title=Renaissance Festivals: Merrying the Past and Present|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|pages=25\u201326|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RseqsimMHGEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA26#v=onepage}}</ref> In 1985, the fair was moved to its current location in Crownsville and in 1986 Smith turned over the management of the fair to his son Jules Smith Jr. who still runs the festival with three siblings.<ref name=\"evans\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Felice |first1=Selene San |title=Renaissance Festival co-founder Jules Smith Sr. dies at 88 |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/obituaries/ac-cn-jules-smith-0911-story.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=capitalgazette.com |publisher=[[Capital Gazette]] |date=10 September 2018}}</ref> The festival was originally an Elizabethan fair, but in 1989 switched to being focused on [[Henry VIII of England]].<ref name=\"evans\" /> King Henry is played by actor Fred Nelson, replacing [[Bill Huttel]], after Huttel's death in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Amanda|title=Fred Nelson - King Henry VIII at Maryland Renaissance Festival, Crownsville|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/magazine/2003/10/19/fred-nelson-king-henry-viii-at-maryland-renaissance-festival-crownsville/b98ca2e1-ddbb-435f-9db7-84d1df751dfc/|website=Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=20 February 2018|date=19 October 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Fair==\n[[File:Maryland Renaissance Festival 2.jpg|thumb|left| [[Theatrical jousting|Jousting]] at the Renaissance Festival]]\nThe [[Tudor style architecture|English Tudor]] village is {{convert|27|acre|m2}}<ref name=\"baltimoresun2018\">{{cite news |last1=Britto |first1=Brittany |title=15 things you're bound to see at the Maryland Renaissance Festival |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-sights-maryland-rennfest-photogallery.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=baltimoresun.com |publisher=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=2018}}</ref> of woods and fields. There are more than 130 [[craft]] shops and 42 food outlets.\n\nMore than 1,300 participants populate the village, 400 work directly for the company, 700 for the other vendors and 200 as performers<ref name=\"capitalgazette2018\">{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |title=Maryland Renaissance Festival: Setting the historical record straight |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/entertainment/ac-en-rennfest-0817-story.html |accessdate=22 October 2018 |work=capitalgazette.com |publisher=[[Capital Gazette]] |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> on stages or as characters throughout the village. The Maryland Renaissance Festival utilizes eight major theaters, four smaller stages in taverns, a children's area and a jousting tiltyard with seating for 3,000.\n\nThe fair contains an elephant and camel that groups of fairgoers pay to ride. In 2014, [[Joan Jett]], speaking on behalf of [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]], wrote a letter asking that the rides be cancelled because of exploitation and abuse associated with using animals in this fashion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joan Jett Urges Maryland Renaissance Festival to End Elephant Rides|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/12659-joan-jett-urges-maryland-renaissance-festival-to-end-elephant-rides|accessdate=10 October 2014|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Born Free USA also protested on a road outside the fair.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gillespie|first1=Paul W.|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/multimedia/photos/cg-maryland-renaissance-festival-opens-picture-015,0,5827027.photo|title=Maryland Renaissance Festival|website=Capital Gazette|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Renaissance fairs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.rennfest.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Coord|39|00|06|N|76|35|01|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark_scale:3000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Festivals in Maryland|Renaissance Festival]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Renaissance fairs]]\n[[Category:Festivals established in 1977]]\n", "name_user": "Freeranging intellect", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFair:Added notable event in 2011", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryland_Renaissance_Festival"}
{"title_page": "Lemon Popsicle", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 Israeli film directed by Boaz Davidson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lemon Popsicle / Hot Bubblegum / Eskimo Limon / Eis am Stiel\n| image          = Lemon Popsicle (film poster).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = [[Yoram Globus]]<br>[[Menahem Golan]]\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson<br>[[Eli Tavor]]\n| starring       = [[Yftach Katzur]]<br>[[Zachi Noy]]<br>[[Jonathan Sagall]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| editing        = Alain Jakubowicz\n| studio         = Noah Films<br>The Cannon Film Group<br>K.F Kinofilm Production (Israel)<br>SCO (West Germany)\n| released       = {{film date|1978|2|11|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew\n| budget         = [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]]3,000,000\n| gross   = [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]]12,500,000 (Israel; 1978)\n| image_size     = 250px\n}}\n'''''Lemon Popsicle''''' (Israeli: '''''Eskimo Limon''''', {{lang-he|\u05d0\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05de\u05d5 \u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}) is a 1978 [[Cinema of West Germany|West German-]][[Cinema of Israel|Israeli]] [[comedy drama film]] co-written and directed by [[Boaz Davidson]]. The success of the film led to a series of sequels.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/132090/Lemon-Popsicle/overview New York Times]</ref> The [[cult film]] follows a group of three teenage boys in the late 1950s [[Tel Aviv]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nSet in Israel in the 1950s, Nili (Niki in the English language release, played by [[Anat Atzmon]]), is the new girl at school. She meets a trio of friends: Benzi (Benji in the English release), Momo (Bobby in the English release) and Yudale (Huey in the English release). Benzi (played by [[Yftach Katzur]]), the typical \"nice guy\" of the group immediately falls in love with Nili. However, Nili prefers the more aggressive and experienced Momo (played by [[Jonathan Sagall]]). Learning that Nili is a virgin, Momo brags to his friends that he will seduce, then dump her, much to Benzi's dismay. However, Benzi is too dependent on his friends and too reluctant to ruin their friendship to warn Nili of Momo's intentions, and must watch as Momo and Nili begin dating. Momo finally takes Nili's virginity, leaving her pregnant. Benzi rushes in to emotionally console Nili and helps her to get an abortion, hoping that she will grow to love him for his support, only to be crushed when Nili and Momo reconcile and resume dating.\n\nThe film contains the memorable{{by whom|date=August 2018}} scene with an older [[Aliyah|olah]] named Stella ([[Ophelia Shtruhl]]) enticing the three boys into having sex with her, earning the nickname \"Stella HaMegameret\" (\"A-cumming Stella\") after she screams \"I'm a-cumming! I'm a-cumming!\" (instead of \"cumming\") during sex because of her poor [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]].\n\n==Release and reception==\n\n===Budget===\nThe picture was produced at a budget of 3 million [[Israeli pound]], of which a million was paid in royalties to the musicians (mostly American) whose songs were used in the soundtrack (such as [[Bill Haley (musician)|Bill Haley]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Gene Vincent]], [[Chuck Berry]] etc.).<ref name = \"A\">Almog, O'z. ''Peridah mi-\u015aeruli\u1e33: shinui \u02bbarakhim ba-eli\u1e6dah ha-Yi\u015bre\u02bcelit''. Zemorah-Bitan (2004). {{ISBN|9789653110519}}. p. 1156</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIt became an immediate commercial success; by December 1978, ''Lemon Popsicle'' sold 1,268,000 tickets in its native country and grossed 12.5 million lira. It was circulated in 700 prints in Europe, where it earned $650,000 during the same period.<ref name = \"B\">''\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05e9\u05e0\u05d4: \u05d0\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05de\u05d5 \u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05df'' ('''Film of the Year: Lemon Popsicle'''). [[Maariv]], 28 December 1978, p. 47.</ref> In total, it sold 1,350,000 tickets in the state, becoming the highest-grossing Israeli picture in history.<ref name = \"A\"/> In [[West Germany]], it reached the 11th place at the 1978 box office, with 2.7 million tickets sold.<ref>''[http://www.insidekino.com/DJahr/D1978.htm Top 50 Deutschland 1978]''. insidekino.com.</ref> ''Lemon Popsicle'' also gained considerable popularity in the rest of Europe and in Japan.<ref>Vasudev, Aruna. ''Being and Becoming: the Cinemas of Asia''. MacMillan (2002). {{ISBN|9780333938201}}. p. 222.</ref> It was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] in the [[36th Golden Globe Awards]], losing to [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s ''[[Autumn Sonata]]''.<ref>''[http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1978 36th Golden Globe Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130414202759/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1978 |date=2013-04-14 }}''. goldenglobes.org.</ref> The film was also selected as the Israeli entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[51st Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nThe series became a success in Germany under the name ''Eis am Stiel''. Most of the films were also dubbed into English and were released in both the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]]. Since the release of ''Lemon Popsicle'', seven official sequels have been made. These were '''''[[Going Steady (1979 film)|Going Steady]]''''' (''Yotzim Kavua'') (1979), ''Hot Bubblegum'' (''Shifshuf Naim'') (1981), ''Private Popsicle'' (''Sapiches'') (1982), ''Baby Love'' (''Sababa'') (1984), ''Up Your Anchor'' (''Harimu Ogen'') (1985), ''Young Love'' (''Ahava Tzeira'') (1987) and ''Summertime Blues'' (''Blues Ba-Kayitz'') (1988). A reboot film, ''The Party Goes On'' (''Hahagiga Nimshehet''), followed in 2001. There's also a spin off movie, ''Private Manoeuvres'' (1983), featuring Zachi Noy.\n\n===Hot Bubblegum===\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Shifshuf Naim\n| image          = \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = [[Yoram Globus]]<br/>[[Menahem Golan]]<br/>Sam Waynberg<br/>Danny Dimbort\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson<br/>Ingo Hermes<br/>Eli Tavor<br/>Sam Waynberg\n| Studio   '     = \n| starring       = \n| music          =\n| cinematography = Amnon Salomon\n| editing        = Jon Koslowsky\n| distributor    =\n| released       = 1981\n| runtime        = \n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n''Hot Bubblegum'' (Hebrew: ''Shifshuf Naim'') is the third film in the ''Lemon Popsicle'' series, set in Tel Aviv and released in 1981.<ref name=\"ifc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.israelfilmcenter.org/israeli-film-database/films/hot-bubblegum |title=Hot Bubblegum |website=israelfilmcenter.org |publisher=The Jewish Community Center in Manhattan}}</ref>\n\n====Synopsis====\nThree high school seniors preparing for final exams in the early 1960s have the normal teenage concerns about girls, sex and relationships. They try to find out if going steady with one girlfriend is better or if changing girlfriends all the time makes for too many complications. By the end of summer, all things get better.<ref name=\"ifc\" />\n\n====Cast====\n* Yftach Katzur as Benzi \n* [[Zachi Noy]] as Yudale \n* [[Jonathan Sagall]] as Momo\n* Dvora Kedar as Sonja\n* Orna Dagan\n* Ariella Rabinovich\n* [[Sibylle Rauch]]\n* [[Christiane Schmidtmer]]\n\n==Remake==\nIn 1982, Davidson wrote and directed an American [[remake]], ''[[The Last American Virgin]]''.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B04E2DA143BF936A25752C0A965948260 New York Times]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Israeli cinema]]\n* [[List of submissions to the 51st Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Israeli submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.lemonpopsicleforever.co.uk Lemon Popsicle Forever]\n* [http://www.wix.com/popsicleape/lemon-popsicle-mag Lemon Popsicle Fanzine]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0079118|title=Eskimo Limon (1) (1978)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0079218|title=Eskimo Limon 2: Yotzim Kavua (1979)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0082528|title=Eskimo Limon 3: Shifshuf Naim (1981)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0084629|title=Eskimo Limon 4: Sapiches (1982)}}\n* Spin-off {{IMDB title|id=0152257|title=Sababa (1983)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0086926|title=Eskimo Limon 5: Roman Za'ir (1984)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0089473|title=Eskimo Limon 6: Harimu Ogen (1985)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0092954|title=Eskimo Limon 7: Ahava Tzeira (1987)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0096190|title=Eskimo Limon 8: Summertime Blues (1988)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0289730|title=Eskimo Limon 9: The Party Goes On (2001)}}\n\n{{Boaz Davidson}}\n\n[[Category:1978 films]]\n[[Category:1970s teen films]]\n[[Category:Israeli films]]\n[[Category:Israeli comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Boaz Davidson]]\n[[Category:Films about virginity]]\n[[Category:Israeli coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Films about abortion]]\n[[Category:Lemon Popsicle]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 Israeli film directed by Boaz Davidson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lemon Popsicle / Hot Bubblegum / Eskimo Limon / Eis am Stiel\n| image          = Lemon Popsicle (film poster).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = [[Yoram Globus]]<br>[[Menahem Golan]]\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson<br>[[Eli Tavor]]\n| starring       = [[Yftach Katzur]]<br>[[Zachi Noy]]<br>[[Jonathan Sagall]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| editing        = Alain Jakubowicz\n| studio         = Noah Films<br>The Cannon Film Group<br>K.F Kinofilm Production (Israel)<br>SCO (West Germany)\n| released       = {{film date|1978|2|11|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew, German\n| budget         = [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]]3,000,000\n| gross   = [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]]12,500,000 (Israel; 1978)\n| image_size     = 250px\n}}\n'''''Lemon Popsicle''''' (Israeli: '''''Eskimo Limon''''', {{lang-he|\u05d0\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05de\u05d5 \u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}) is a 1978 [[Cinema of West Germany|West German-]][[Cinema of Israel|Israeli]] [[comedy drama film]] co-written and directed by [[Boaz Davidson]]. The success of the film led to a series of sequels.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/132090/Lemon-Popsicle/overview New York Times]</ref> The [[cult film]] follows a group of three teenage boys in the late 1950s [[Tel Aviv]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nSet in Israel in the 1950s, Nili (Niki in the English language release, played by [[Anat Atzmon]]), is the new girl at school. She meets a trio of friends: Benzi (Benji in the English release), Momo (Bobby in the English release) and Yudale (Huey in the English release). Benzi (played by [[Yftach Katzur]]), the typical \"nice guy\" of the group immediately falls in love with Nili. However, Nili prefers the more aggressive and experienced Momo (played by [[Jonathan Sagall]]). Learning that Nili is a virgin, Momo brags to his friends that he will seduce, then dump her, much to Benzi's dismay. However, Benzi is too dependent on his friends and too reluctant to ruin their friendship to warn Nili of Momo's intentions, and must watch as Momo and Nili begin dating. Momo finally takes Nili's virginity, leaving her pregnant. Benzi rushes in to emotionally console Nili and helps her to get an abortion, hoping that she will grow to love him for his support, only to be crushed when Nili and Momo reconcile and resume dating.\n\nThe film contains the memorable{{by whom|date=August 2018}} scene with an older [[Aliyah|olah]] named Stella ([[Ophelia Shtruhl]]) enticing the three boys into having sex with her, earning the nickname \"Stella HaMegameret\" (\"A-cumming Stella\") after she screams \"I'm a-cumming! I'm a-cumming!\" (instead of \"cumming\") during sex because of her poor [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]].\n\n==Release and reception==\n\n===Budget===\nThe picture was produced at a budget of 3 million [[Israeli pound]], of which a million was paid in royalties to the musicians (mostly American) whose songs were used in the soundtrack (such as [[Bill Haley (musician)|Bill Haley]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Gene Vincent]], [[Chuck Berry]] etc.).<ref name = \"A\">Almog, O'z. ''Peridah mi-\u015aeruli\u1e33: shinui \u02bbarakhim ba-eli\u1e6dah ha-Yi\u015bre\u02bcelit''. Zemorah-Bitan (2004). {{ISBN|9789653110519}}. p. 1156</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIt became an immediate commercial success; by December 1978, ''Lemon Popsicle'' sold 1,268,000 tickets in its native country and grossed 12.5 million lira. It was circulated in 700 prints in Europe, where it earned $650,000 during the same period.<ref name = \"B\">''\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05e9\u05e0\u05d4: \u05d0\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05de\u05d5 \u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05df'' ('''Film of the Year: Lemon Popsicle'''). [[Maariv]], 28 December 1978, p. 47.</ref> In total, it sold 1,350,000 tickets in the state, becoming the highest-grossing Israeli picture in history.<ref name = \"A\"/> In [[West Germany]], it reached the 11th place at the 1978 box office, with 2.7 million tickets sold.<ref>''[http://www.insidekino.com/DJahr/D1978.htm Top 50 Deutschland 1978]''. insidekino.com.</ref> ''Lemon Popsicle'' also gained considerable popularity in the rest of Europe and in Japan.<ref>Vasudev, Aruna. ''Being and Becoming: the Cinemas of Asia''. MacMillan (2002). {{ISBN|9780333938201}}. p. 222.</ref> It was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] in the [[36th Golden Globe Awards]], losing to [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s ''[[Autumn Sonata]]''.<ref>''[http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1978 36th Golden Globe Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130414202759/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1978 |date=2013-04-14 }}''. goldenglobes.org.</ref> The film was also selected as the Israeli entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[51st Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nThe series became a success in Germany under the name ''Eis am Stiel''. Most of the films were also dubbed into English and were released in both the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]]. Since the release of ''Lemon Popsicle'', seven official sequels have been made. These were '''''[[Going Steady (1979 film)|Going Steady]]''''' (''Yotzim Kavua'') (1979), ''Hot Bubblegum'' (''Shifshuf Naim'') (1981), ''Private Popsicle'' (''Sapiches'') (1982), ''Baby Love'' (''Sababa'') (1984), ''Up Your Anchor'' (''Harimu Ogen'') (1985), ''Young Love'' (''Ahava Tzeira'') (1987) and ''Summertime Blues'' (''Blues Ba-Kayitz'') (1988). A reboot film, ''The Party Goes On'' (''Hahagiga Nimshehet''), followed in 2001. There's also a spin off movie, ''Private Manoeuvres'' (1983), featuring Zachi Noy.\n\n===Hot Bubblegum===\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Shifshuf Naim\n| image          = \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = [[Yoram Globus]]<br/>[[Menahem Golan]]<br/>Sam Waynberg<br/>Danny Dimbort\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson<br/>Ingo Hermes<br/>Eli Tavor<br/>Sam Waynberg\n| Studio   '     = \n| starring       = \n| music          =\n| cinematography = Amnon Salomon\n| editing        = Jon Koslowsky\n| distributor    =\n| released       = 1981\n| runtime        = \n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n''Hot Bubblegum'' (Hebrew: ''Shifshuf Naim'') is the third film in the ''Lemon Popsicle'' series, set in Tel Aviv and released in 1981.<ref name=\"ifc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.israelfilmcenter.org/israeli-film-database/films/hot-bubblegum |title=Hot Bubblegum |website=israelfilmcenter.org |publisher=The Jewish Community Center in Manhattan}}</ref>\n\n====Synopsis====\nThree high school seniors preparing for final exams in the early 1960s have the normal teenage concerns about girls, sex and relationships. They try to find out if going steady with one girlfriend is better or if changing girlfriends all the time makes for too many complications. By the end of summer, all things get better.<ref name=\"ifc\" />\n\n====Cast====\n* Yftach Katzur as Benzi \n* [[Zachi Noy]] as Yudale \n* [[Jonathan Sagall]] as Momo\n* Dvora Kedar as Sonja\n* Orna Dagan\n* Ariella Rabinovich\n* [[Sibylle Rauch]]\n* [[Christiane Schmidtmer]]\n\n==Remake==\nIn 1982, Davidson wrote and directed an American [[remake]], ''[[The Last American Virgin]]''.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B04E2DA143BF936A25752C0A965948260 New York Times]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Israeli cinema]]\n* [[List of submissions to the 51st Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Israeli submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.lemonpopsicleforever.co.uk Lemon Popsicle Forever]\n* [http://www.wix.com/popsicleape/lemon-popsicle-mag Lemon Popsicle Fanzine]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0079118|title=Eskimo Limon (1) (1978)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0079218|title=Eskimo Limon 2: Yotzim Kavua (1979)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0082528|title=Eskimo Limon 3: Shifshuf Naim (1981)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0084629|title=Eskimo Limon 4: Sapiches (1982)}}\n* 